#:~:text=if%20so%2C,.%20
Text:  If so, how delightful for them, and we shall all breathe a sigh of relief, but there will be no story. 
Audio: If so, how delightful for them. And we shall all breathe a sigh of relief. But there will be no story.

#:~:text=on%20the%20other%20hand%2C%20i,.%20
Text:  On the other hand, if they are not in time, I solemnly promise that it will all come right in the end.
Audio: On the other hand, if they are not in time, I solemnly promise that it will all come right in the end.

#:~:text=they%20would%20have%20r,.%20
Text:  They would have reached the nursery in time had it not been that the little stars were watching them. 
Audio: They would have reached the nursery in time, had it not been that the little stars were watching them.

#:~:text=once%20ag,%3A%20
Text:  Once again the stars blew the window open, and that smallest star of all called out:
Audio: Once again the stars blew the window open, and that smallest star of all called out,

#:~:text='cav,!
Text:  'Cave, Peter!
Audio: 

#:~:text=ter!-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: Peter.

#:~:text=then%20peter%20knew,.%20
Text:  Then Peter knew that there was not a moment to lose. 
Audio: Then Peter knew that there was not a moment to lose.

#:~:text='come%2C,.%20
Text:  'Come,' he cried imperiously, and soared out at once into the night, followed by John and Michael and Wendy.
Audio: Come, he cried imperiously, and soared out at once into the night, followed by John and Michael and Wendy.

#:~:text=mr.%20and%20mrs.%20darling%20and%20nana%20r,.%20
Text:  Mr. and Mrs. Darling and Nana rushed into the nursery too late. 
Audio: Mr. and Mrs. Darling and Nana rushed into the nursery too late.

#:~:text=the%20birds%20were%20flown.
Text:  The birds were flown.
Audio: The birds were flown. End of chapter 3

#:~:text=.%20-,chapter%20iv%20
Text:  CHAPTER IV
Audio: CHAPTER IV.

#:~:text=chapter%20iv%20-,the%20flight%20
Text:  THE FLIGHT
Audio: THE FLIGHT.

#:~:text='second%20to%20the%20right%2C%20,.
Text:  'Second to the right, and straight on till morning.
Audio: SECOND TO THE RIGHT, AND STRAIGHT ON TILL MORNING.

#:~:text=ng.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=that%2C%20p,.%20
Text:  That, Peter had told Wendy, was the way to the Neverland; but even birds, carrying maps and consulting them at windy corners, could not have sighted it with these instructions. 
Audio: THAT, PETER HAD TOLD WENDY, WAS THE WAY TO THE NEVERLAND. BUT EVEN BIRDS, CARRIING MAPS AND CONSULTING THEM AT WENDY CORNERS, CANNOT HAVE CITED IT WITH THESE INSTRUCTIONS.

#:~:text=peter%2C%20y,.%20
Text:  Peter, you see, just said anything that came into his head.
Audio: PETER, YOU SEE, JUST SAID ANYTHING THAT CAME INTO HIS HEAD.

#:~:text=at%20first%20hi,.%20
Text:  At first his companions trusted him implicitly, and so great were the delights of flying that they wasted time circling round church spires or any other tall objects on the way that took their fancy.
Audio: AT FIRST, HIS COMPANIONS TRUSTED HIM IMPLICITLY, AND SO GREAT WERE THE DELIGHTS OF FLYING THAT THEY WASTED TIME CIRCLING ROUND CHURCH SPIRES OR ANY OTHER TALL OBJECTS ON THE WAY THAT TOOK THE FANCI.

#:~:text=john%20and%20michael%20r,.%20
Text:  John and Michael raced, Michael getting a start.
Audio: JOHN AND MICHAEL RACED. MICHAEL GETTING A START.

#:~:text=they%20rec,.%20
Text:  They recalled with contempt that not so long ago they had thought themselves fine fellows for being able to fly round a room.
Audio: THEY RECALLED WITH CONTEMPT THAT NOT SO LONG AGO THEY HAD THOUGHT THEMSELVES FINE FELLOWS FOR BEING ABLE TO FLY AROUND A ROOM.

#:~:text=not%20so%20long%20ago.
Text:  Not so long ago. 
Audio: NOT LONG AGO

#:~:text=but%20how%20l,%3F%20
Text:  But how long ago? 
Audio: BUT HOW LONG AGO?

#:~:text=they%20were%20fl,.%20
Text:  They were flying over the sea before this thought began to disturb Wendy seriously. 
Audio: THEY WERE FLYING OVER THE SEA BEFORE THIS THOUGHT BEGAN TO DISTURB WENDY SERIOUSLY.

#:~:text=john%20tho,.%20
Text:  John thought it was their second sea and their third night.
Audio: JOHN THOUGHT IT WAS THEIR SECOND SEA AND THEIR THIRD NIGHT.

#:~:text=sometimes%20it,.%20
Text:  Sometimes it was dark and sometimes light, and now they were very cold and again too warm. 
Audio: SOMETIMES IT WAS DARK AND SOMETIMES LIGHT AND NOW THEY WERE VERY COLD AND AGAIN TOO WARM.

#:~:text=did%20they%20r,%3F%20
Text:  Did they really feel hungry at times, or were they merely pretending, because Peter had such a jolly new way of feeding them? 
Audio: SOMETIMES IT WASN'T. HANGRY AT TIMES OR WERE THEY MERELY PRETENDING BECAUSE PETER HAD SUCH A JOLY NEW WAY OF FEEDING THEM.

#:~:text=his%20way%20was%20t,.%20
Text:  His way was to pursue birds who had food in their mouths suitable for humans and snatch it from them; then the birds would follow and snatch it back; and they would all go chasing each other gaily for miles, parting at last with mutual expressions of good-will. 
Audio: HIS WAY WAS TO PURSUE BIRDS WHO HAD FOOD IN THEIR MOUTHS SUITABLE FOR HUMANS AND SNATCH IT FROM THEM. THEN THE BIRDS WOULD FOLLOW AND SNATCH IT BACK AND THEY WOULD ALL GO CHASING EACH OTHER GAYLY FOR MILES PARTING AT LAST WITH MUTUAL EXPRESSIONS OF GOOD WILL

#:~:text=but%20wendy%20n,.%20
Text:  But Wendy noticed with gentle concern that Peter did not seem to know that this was rather an odd way of getting your bread and butter, nor even that there are other ways.
Audio: BUT WENDY NOTICED WITH GENTLE CONCERN THAT PETER DID NOT SEEM TO KNOW THAT THIS WAS RATHER AN ODD WAY OF GETTING YOUR BREAD AND BUTTER NOR EVEN THAT THERE WERE OTHER WAYS

#:~:text=certainly%20t,.%20
Text:  Certainly they did not pretend to be sleepy, they were sleepy; and that was a danger, for the moment they popped off, down they fell. 
Audio: CERTAINLY THEY DID NOT PRETEND TO BE SLEEPY THEY WERE SLEEPY AND THAT WAS A DANGER FOR THE MOMENT THEY POPPED OFF DOWN THEY FELL

#:~:text=the%20awful%20thing%20,.%20
Text:  The awful thing was that Peter thought this funny.
Audio: THE AWFUL THING WAS THAT PETER THOUGHT THIS FUNNY

#:~:text='there%20h,!
Text:  'There he goes again!
Audio: THERE HE GOES AGAIN

#:~:text='%20he%20would%20c,.%20
Text:  ' he would cry gleefully, as Michael suddenly dropped like a stone.
Audio: HE WOULD CRY GLEEFULLY AS MICHAEL SUDDENLY DROPPED LIKE A STONE

#:~:text='save%20h,!
Text:  'Save him, save him!
Audio: SAVE HIM SAVE HIM

#:~:text='%20cried%20wendy%2C%20l,.%20
Text:  ' cried Wendy, looking with horror at the cruel sea far below. 
Audio: CRIED WENDY LOOKING WITH HORROR AT THE CRUEL SEA FAR BELOW

#:~:text=eventu,.%20
Text:  Eventually Peter would dive through the air, and catch Michael just before he could strike the sea, and it was lovely the way he did it; but he always waited till the last moment, and you felt it was his cleverness that interested him and not the saving of human life. 
Audio: EVENTUALLY PETER WOULD DIVE THROUGH THE AIR AND CATCH MICHAEL JUST BEFORE HE COULD STRIKE THE SEA AND IT WAS LOVELY THE WAY HE DID IT BUT HE ALWAYS WAITED TO THE LAST MOMENT AND YOU FELT IT WAS HIS CLEVERNESS THAT INTERESTED HIM AND NOT THE SAVING OF HUMAN LIFE

#:~:text=also%20h,.%20
Text:  Also he was fond of variety, and the sport that engrossed him one moment would suddenly cease to engage him, so there was always the possibility that the next time you fell he would let you go.
Audio: ALSO HE WAS FOND OF VARIETY AND THE SPORT THAT ENGROSSED HIM ONE MOMENT WOULD SUDDENLY CEASE TO ENGAGE HIM SO THERE WAS ALWAYS THE POSSIBILITY THAT THE NEXT TIME YOU FELL HE WOULD LET YOU GO

#:~:text=he%20could%20sl,.%20
Text:  He could sleep in the air without falling, by merely lying on his back and floating, but this was, partly at least, because he was so light that if you got behind him and blew he went faster.
Audio: HE COULD SLEEP IN THE AIR WITHOUT FALLING BY MERELY LYING ON HIS BACK AND FLOATING BUT THIS WAS PARTLY AT LEAST BECAUSE HE WAS SO LIGHT THAT IF HE GOT BEHIND HIM IN BLUE HE WENT FASTER

#:~:text='do%20b,.
Text:  'Do be more polite to him,' Wendy whispered to John, when they were playing 'Follow my Leader.
Audio: DO BE MORE POLITE TO HIM WENDY WHISPERED TO JOHN WHEN THEY WERE PLAYING FOLLOW MY LEADER

#:~:text=der.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='then%20tell%20hi,.%20
Text:  'Then tell him to stop showing off,' said John.
Audio: THEN TELL HIM TO STOP SHOWING OFF SAID JOHN WHEN PLAYING FOLLOW MY LEADER

#:~:text=when%20pl,.%20
Text:  When playing Follow my Leader, Peter would fly close to the water and touch each shark's tail in passing, just as in the street you may run your finger along an iron railing. 
Audio: JOHN WHEN PLAYING FOLLOW MY LEADER PETER WOULD FLY CLOSE TO THE WATER AND TOUCH EACH SHARK'S TAIL IN PASSING JUST AS IN THE STREET YOU MAY RUN YOUR FINGER ALONG AN IRON RAILING

#:~:text=they%20could%20not%20f,.%20
Text:  They could not follow him in this with much success, so perhaps it was rather like showing off, especially as he kept looking behind to see how many tails they missed.
Audio: THEY CANNOT FOLLOW HIM IN THIS WITH MUCH SUCCESS SO PERHAPS IT WAS RATHER LIKE SHOWING OFF ESPECIALLY AS HE KEPT LOOKING BEHIND TO SEE HOW MANY TAILS THEY MISSED

#:~:text='you%20must%20b,.%20
Text:  'You must be nice to him,' Wendy impressed on her brothers. 
Audio: YOU MUST BE NICE TO HIM WENDY IMPRESSED UPON HER BROTHERS

#:~:text='what%20c,%3F
Text:  'What could we do if he were to leave us?
Audio: 

#:~:text=us%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: COULD WE DO IF HE WERE TO LEAVE US

#:~:text='we%20could%20g,.%20
Text:  'We could go back,' Michael said.
Audio: WE COULD GO BACK MICHAEL SAID

#:~:text='how%20co,%3F
Text:  'How could we ever find our way back without him?
Audio: 

#:~:text=im%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: COULD WE EVER FIND OUR WAY BACK WITHOUT HIM

#:~:text='well%2C%20then%2C%20w,.%20
Text:  'Well, then, we could go on,' said John.
Audio: WELL THEN WE COULD GO ON SAID JOHN

#:~:text='that%20is%20t,.%20
Text:  'That is the awful thing, John. 
Audio: THAT IS THE AWFUL THING JOHN

#:~:text=we%20should%20have%20t,.
Text:  We should have to go on, for we don't know how to stop.
Audio: WE SHOULD HAVE TO GO ON FOR WE DON'T KNOW HOW TO STOP

#:~:text=top.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=this%20was%20true%3B,.%20
Text:  This was true; Peter had forgotten to show them how to stop.
Audio: THIS WAS TRUE PETER HAD FORGOTTEN TO SHOW THEM HOW TO STOP

#:~:text=john%20said%20t,.%20
Text:  John said that if the worst came to the worst, all they had to do was to go straight on, for the world was round, and so in time they must come back to their own window.
Audio: JOHN SAID THAT IF THE WORST CAME TO THE WORST ALL THEY HAD TO DO WAS TO GO STRAIGHT ON FOR THE WORLD WAS ROUND AND SO IN TIME THEY MUST COME BACK TO THEIR OWN WINDOW

#:~:text='and%20wh,%3F
Text:  'And who is to get food for us, John?
Audio: 

#:~:text=hn%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: WHO IS TO GET FOOD FOR US JOHN

#:~:text='i%20n,.
Text:  'I nipped a bit out of that eagle's mouth pretty neatly, Wendy.
Audio: I NIPPED A BIT OUT OF THAT EAGLE'S MOUTH PRETTY NEATLY WENDY

#:~:text=dy.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='af,.%20
Text:  'After the twentieth try,' Wendy reminded him. 
Audio: AFTER THE TWENTIETH TRY WENDY REMINDED HIM

#:~:text='and%20e,.
Text:  'And even though we became good at picking up food, see how we bump against clouds and things if he is not near to give us a hand.
Audio: AND EVEN THOUGH WE BECAME GOOD AT PICKING UP FOOD SEE HOW WE BUMP AGAINST CLOUDS AND THINGS IF HE IS NOT NEAR TO GIVE US A HAND

#:~:text=nd.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=indeed%20they%20we,.%20
Text:  Indeed they were constantly bumping. 
Audio: INDEED THEY WERE CONSTANTLY BUMPING

#:~:text=they%20could%20now,.%20
Text:  They could now fly strongly, though they still kicked far too much; but if they saw a cloud in front of them, the more they tried to avoid it, the more certainly did they bump into it. 
Audio: THEY COULD NOW FLY STRONGLY THOUGH THEY STILL KICKED FAR TOO MUCH BUT IF THEY SAW A CLOUD IN FRONT OF THEM THE MORE THEY TRIED TO AVOID IT THE MORE CERTAINLY DID THEY BUMP INTO IT

#:~:text=if%20n,.%20
Text:  If Nana had been with them, she would have had a bandage round Michael's forehead by this time.
Audio: IF NANA HAD BEEN WITH THEM SHE WOULD HAVE HAD A BANDAGE ROUND MICHAEL'S FOREHEAD BY THIS TIME

#:~:text=peter%20was%20n,.%20
Text:  Peter was not with them for the moment, and they felt rather lonely up there by themselves. 
Audio: PETER WAS NOT WITH THEM FOR THE MOMENT AND THEY FELT RATHER LONELY UP THERE BY THEMSELVES

#:~:text=he%20could%20g,.%20
Text:  He could go so much faster than they that he would suddenly shoot out of sight, to have some adventure in which they had no share. 
Audio: HE COULD GO SO MUCH FASTER THAN THEY THAT HE WOULD SUDDENLY SHOOT OUT OF SIGHT TO HAVE SOME ADVENTURE IN WHICH THEY HAD NO SHARE

#:~:text=he%20would%20come%20d,.%20
Text:  He would come down laughing over something fearfully funny he had been saying to a star, but he had already forgotten what it was, or he would come up with mermaid scales still sticking to him, and yet not be able to say for certain what had been happening. 
Audio: HE WOULD COME DOWN LAUGHING OVER SOMETHING FEARFULLY FUNNY HE HAD BEEN SAYING TO A STAR BUT HE HAD ALREADY FORGOTTEN WHAT IT WAS OR HE WOULD COME UP WITH MERMAID SCALE STILL STICKING TO HIM AND YET NOT BE ABLE TO SAY FOR CERTAIN WHAT HAD BEEN HAPPENING

#:~:text=it%20was%20really%20r,.%20
Text:  It was really rather irritating to children who had never seen a mermaid.
Audio: IT WAS REALLY RATHER IRRITATING TO CHILDREN WHO HAD NEVER SEEN A MERMAID

#:~:text='and%20if,%3F
Text:  'And if he forgets them, so quickly,' Wendy argued, 'how can we expect that he will go on remembering us?
Audio: AND IF HE FORGETS THEM SO QUICKLY WENDY ARGUED HOW CAN WE EXPECT HE WILL GO ON REMEMBRING US

#:~:text=us%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=indeed%2C,.%20
Text:  Indeed, sometimes when he returned he did not remember them, at least not well. 
Audio: INDEED SOMETIMES WHEN HE RETURNED HE DID NOT REMEMBER THEM AT LEAST NOT WELL

#:~:text=wendy%20was%20su,.%20
Text:  Wendy was sure of it. 
Audio: WENDY WAS SURE OF IT

#:~:text=she%20saw%20r,.%20
Text:  She saw recognition come into his eyes as he was about to pass them the time of day and go on; once even she had to tell him her name.
Audio: SHE SAW RECOGNITION COME INTO HIS EYES AS HE WAS ABOUT TO PASS THEM THE TIME OF DAY AND GO ON ON ONCE EVEN SHE HAD TO CALL HIM BY NAME

#:~:text='i'm%20w,.%20
Text:  'I'm Wendy,' she said agitatedly.
Audio: I'M WENDY SHE SAID AGITATEDLY

#:~:text=he%20was%20very%20s,%20
Text:  He was very sorry. 
Audio: HE WAS VERY SORRY

#:~:text='i%20say%2C%20w,.
Text:  'I say, Wendy,' he whispered to her, 'always if you see me forgetting you, just keep on saying "I'm Wendy," and then I'll remember.
Audio: I SAY WENDY HE WHISPERED TO HER ALWAYS IF YOU SEE ME FORGETTING YOU JUST KEEP ON SAYING I'M WENDY AND THEN I'LL REMEMBER

#:~:text=ber.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=of%20course%20thi,.%20
Text:  Of course this was rather unsatisfactory. 
Audio: OF COURSE THIS WAS RATHER UNSATISFACTORY

#:~:text=however%2C%20to,.%20
Text:  However, to make amends he showed them how to lie out flat on a strong wind that was going their way, and this was such a pleasant change that they tried it several times and found they could sleep thus with security. 
Audio: HOWEVER TO MAKE AMENDS HE SHOWED THEM HOW TO LIE OUT FLAT ON A STRONG WIND THAT WAS GOING THEIR WAY AND THIS WAS SUCH A PLEASANT CHANGE THAT THEY TRIED IT SEVERAL TIMES AND FOUND THAT THEY COULD SLEEP THUS WITH SECURITY

#:~:text=indeed%20they%20wo,.
Text:  Indeed they would have slept longer, but Peter tired quickly of sleeping, and soon he would cry in his captain voice, 'We get off here.
Audio: INDEED THEY WOULD HAVE SLEEPT LONGER BUT PETER TIRED QUICKLY OF SLEEPING AND SOON HE WOULD CRY IN HIS CAPTAIN VOICE WE GET OFF HERE

#:~:text='%20so%20,.%20
Text:  ' So with occasional tiffs, but on the whole rollicking, they drew near the Neverland; for after many moons they did reach it, and, what is more, they had been going pretty straight all the time, not perhaps so much owing to the guidance of Peter or Tink as because the island was out looking for them. 
Audio: SO WITH OCCASIONAL TIFFS BUT ON THE WHOLE ROLLICKING THEY DREW NEAR THE NEVERLAND FOR AFTER MANY MOONS DID THEY REACH IT AND WHAT IS MORE THEY HAD BEEN GOING PRETTY STRAIGHT ALL THE TIME NOT PERHAPS SO MUCH OING TO THE GUIDANCE OF PETER OR TINK AS BECAUSE THE ISLAND WAS LOOKING FOR

#:~:text=it%20is%20o,.%20
Text:  It is only thus that any one may sight those magic shores.
Audio: IT WAS ONLY THUS THAT ANYONE MAY SITE THOSE MAGIC SHORES

#:~:text='there%20it,.%20
Text:  'There it is,' said Peter calmly.
Audio: THERE IT IS SAID PETER CALMLY

#:~:text='where%2C,%3F
Text:  'Where, where?
Audio: WHERE WHERE

#:~:text=ere%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='where%20al,.
Text:  'Where all the arrows are pointing.
Audio: WHERE ALL THE ARROWS ARE POINTING

#:~:text=ng.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=indeed%20a%20,.%20
Text:  Indeed a million golden arrows were pointing out the island to the children, all directed by their friend the sun, who wanted them to be sure of their way before leaving them for the night.
Audio: INDEED A MILLION GOLDEN ARROWS WERE POINTING IT OUT TO THE CHILDREN ALL DIRECTED BY THEIR FRIEND THE SUN WHO WANTED THEM TO BE SURE OF THEIR WAY BEFORE LEAVING THEM FOR THE NIGHT

#:~:text=wendy%20and%20john%20and%20michael%20s,.%20
Text:  Wendy and John and Michael stood on tiptoe in the air to get their first sight of the island. 
Audio: WENDY AND JOHN AND MICHAEL STOOD ON TIPTOE IN THE AIR TO GET THEIR FIRST SIGHT OF THE ISLAND

#:~:text=strange%20t,.%20
Text:  Strange to say, they all recognised it at once, and until fear fell upon them they hailed it, not as something long dreamt of and seen at last, but as a familiar friend to whom they were returning home for the holidays.
Audio: STRANGE TO SAY THEY ALL RECOGNIZED IT AT ONCE AND UNTIL FEAR FELL UPON THEM THEY HAILED IT NOT AS SOMETHING LONG DREAMED OF AND SEEN AT LAST BUT AS A FAMILIAR FRIEND TO WHOM THEY WERE RETURNING HOME FOR THE HOLIDAYS

#:~:text='john%2C%20t,.
Text:  'John, there's the lagoon.
Audio: 

#:~:text=oon.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: THERE IS THE LAGOON

#:~:text='wendy%2C%20l,.
Text:  'Wendy, look at the turtles burying their eggs in the sand.
Audio: WENDY LOOK AT THE TURTLES BURNING THEIR EGGS IN THE SAND

#:~:text=nd.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='i%20say%2C%20john%2C%20,.
Text:  'I say, John, I see your flamingo with the broken leg.
Audio: I SAY JOHN I SEE YOUR FLAMINGO WITH A BROKEN LEG

#:~:text=leg.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='look%2C,.
Text:  'Look, Michael, there's your cave.
Audio: LOOK MICHAEL THERE'S YOUR CAVE

#:~:text=ve.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='john%2C%20w,%3F
Text:  'John, what's that in the brushwood?
Audio: 

#:~:text=ood%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: WHAT'S THAT IN THE BRUSHWOOD

#:~:text='it's%20a%20w,.%20
Text:  'It's a wolf with her whelps. 
Audio: IT'S A WOLF WITH HER WELPS

#:~:text=wendy%2C%20i%20d,.
Text:  Wendy, I do believe that's your little whelp.
Audio: WENDY I DO BELIEVE THAT'S YOUR LITTLE WELP

#:~:text=elp.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='there's%20m,.
Text:  'There's my boat, John, with her sides stove in.
Audio: THERE'S MY BOAT JOHN WITH HER SIDE STOVE IN

#:~:text=%20in.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='no%2C%20it%20isn't.
Text:  'No, it isn't. 
Audio: NO IT ISN'T

#:~:text=why%2C%20we,.
Text:  Why, we burned your boat.
Audio: 

#:~:text=oat.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: WE BURNED YOUR BOAT

#:~:text='that's%20he,.%20
Text:  'That's her, at any rate. 
Audio: THAT'S HER AT ANY RATE

#:~:text=i%20say%2C%20john%2C%20i%20see%20t,.
Text:  I say, John, I see the smoke of the redskin camp.
Audio: I SAY JOHN I SEE THE SMOKE OF THE REDSKIN CAMP

#:~:text=mp.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='where%3F
Text:  'Where? 
Audio: WHERE

#:~:text=show%20m,.
Text:  Show me, and I'll tell you by the way the smoke curls whether they are on the war-path.
Audio: SHOW ME AND I'LL TELL YOU BY THE WAY SMOKE CURLS WHETHER THEY'RE ON THE WAR PATH

#:~:text=th.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='there%2C%20j,.
Text:  'There, just across the Mysterious River.
Audio: THERE JUST ACROSS THE MYSTERIOUS RIVER

#:~:text=iver.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='i%20se,.%20
Text:  'I see now. 
Audio: I SEE NOW

#:~:text=yes%2C%20they,.
Text:  Yes, they are on the war-path right enough.
Audio: YES THEY ARE ON THE WAR PATH RIGHT ENOUGH

#:~:text=gh.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=peter%20was%20a,%3F%20
Text:  Peter was a little annoyed with them for knowing so much; but if he wanted to lord it over them his triumph was at hand, for have I not told you that anon fear fell upon them?
Audio: PETER WAS A LITTLE ANOID WITH THEM FOR KNOWING SO MUCH BUT IF HE WANTED TO LORD IT OVER THEM HIS TRIUMPH WAS AT HAND FOR HAVE I NOT TOLD YOU THAT ANON FEAR FELL UPON THEM

#:~:text=it%20came%20as,.%20
Text:  It came as the arrows went, leaving the island in gloom.
Audio: IT CAME AS THE ARROWS WENT LEAVING THE ISLAND IN GLOOM

#:~:text=in%20the%20ol,.%20
Text:  In the old days at home the Neverland had always begun to look a little dark and threatening by bedtime. 
Audio: IN THE OLD DAYS AT HOME THE NEVERLAND HAD ALWAYS BEGUN TO LOOK A LITTLE DARK AND THREATENING BY BEDTIME

#:~:text=then%20u,.%20
Text:  Then unexplored patches arose in it and spread; black shadows moved about in them; the roar of the beasts of prey was quite different now, and above all, you lost the certainty that you would win. 
Audio: THEN UNEXPLORED PATCHES AROSE IN IT AND SPREAD BLACK SHADOWS MOVED ABOUT IN THEM THE ROAR OF THE BEASTS OF PREY WAS QUITE DIFFERENT NOW AND ABOVE ALL YOU LOST THE CERTAINTY THAT YOU WOULD WIN

#:~:text=you%20were%20q,.%20
Text:  You were quite glad that the night-lights were in. 
Audio: YOU WERE QUITE GLAD THAT THE NIGHTLIGHTS WERE ON

#:~:text=you%20e,.%20
Text:  You even liked Nana to say that this was just the mantelpiece over here, and that the Neverland was all make-believe.
Audio: YOU EVEN LIKED NANA TO SAY THAT THIS WAS JUST THE MANTELPIECE OVER HERE AND THAT THE NEVERLAND WAS ALL MAKE-BELIEVE

#:~:text=of%20course%20the%20neverland%20,%3F%20
Text:  Of course the Neverland had been make-believe in those days; but it was real now, and there were no night-lights, and it was getting darker every moment, and where was Nana?
Audio: OF COURSE THE NEVERLAND HAD BEEN MAKE-BELIEVE IN THOSE DAYS BUT IT WAS REAL NOW AND THERE WERE NO NIGHTLIGHTS AND IT WAS GETTING DARKER EVERY MOMENT AND WHERE WAS NANA

#:~:text=they%20had%20been%20f,.%20
Text:  They had been flying apart, but they huddled close to Peter now. 
Audio: THEY HAD BEEN FLYING APART BUT THEY HUDDLED CLOSE TO PETER NOW

#:~:text=his%20carel,.%20
Text:  His careless manner had gone at last, his eyes were sparkling, and a tingle went through them every time they touched his body. 
Audio: HIS CARELESS MANNER HAD GONE AT LAST HIS EYES WERE SPARKLING AND A TINGLE WENT THROUGH THEM EVERY TIME THEY TOUCHED HIS BODY

#:~:text=they%20were%20now,.%20
Text:  They were now over the fearsome island, flying so low that sometimes a tree grazed their feet. 
Audio: THEY WERE NOW OVER THE FEARSOME ISLAND FLYING SO LOW THAT SOMETIMES A TREE GRAZED THEIR FEET

#:~:text=nothing%20h,.%20
Text:  Nothing horrid was visible in the air, yet their progress had become slow and laboured, exactly as if they were pushing their way through hostile forces. 
Audio: NOTHING HORRID WAS VISIBLE IN THE AIR YET THEIR PROGRESS HAD BECOME SLOW AND LABORED EXACTLY AS IF THEY WERE PUSHING THEIR WAY THROUGH HOSTILE FORCES

#:~:text=sometimes%20they,.%20
Text:  Sometimes they hung in the air until Peter had beaten on it with his fists.
Audio: SOMETIMES THEY HUNG IN THE AIR UNTIL PETER HAD BEATEN ON IT WITH HIS FISTS

#:~:text='they%20d,.%20
Text:  'They don't want us to land,' he explained.
Audio: THEY DON'T WANT US TO LAND HE EXPLAINED

#:~:text=.%20-,'who%20are%20they%3F
Text:  'Who are they?
Audio: WHO ARE THEY

#:~:text='%20wendy%20whispered%2C,%20
Text:  ' Wendy whispered, shuddering.
Audio: WENDY WHISPERED SHUTTERING

#:~:text=but%20he%20c,.%20
Text:  But he could not or would not say. 
Audio: BUT HE COULD NOT OR WOULD NOT SAY

#:~:text=tinker%20bell%20had,.%20
Text:  Tinker Bell had been asleep on his shoulder, but now he wakened her and sent her on in front.
Audio: TINKERBELL HAD BEEN ASLEEP ON HIS SHOULDER BUT NOW HE WAKENED HER AND SENT HER ON IN FRONT

#:~:text=sometimes%20he,.%20
Text:  Sometimes he poised himself in the air, listening intently with his hand to his ear, and again he would stare down with eyes so bright that they seemed to bore two holes to earth. 
Audio: SOMETIMES HE POISED HIMSELF IN THE AIR LISTENING INTENTLY WITH HIS HAND TO HIS EAR AND AGAIN HE WOULD STARE DOWN WITH EYES SO BRIGHT THAT THEY SEEMED TO BOARD TWO HOLES TO EARTH

#:~:text=having%20d,.%20
Text:  Having done these things, he went on again.
Audio: HAVING DONE THESE THINGS HE WENT ON AGAIN

#:~:text=his%20cour,.%20
Text:  His courage was almost appalling. 
Audio: HIS COURAGE WAS ALMOST APPALLING

#:~:text='do%20you%20w,%3F
Text:  'Do you want an adventure now,' he said casually to John, 'or would you like to have your tea first?
Audio: WOULD YOU LIKE AN ADVENTURE NOW HE SAID CASUALLY TO JOHN OR WOULD YOU LIKE TO HAVE YOUR TEA FIRST

#:~:text=st%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=wendy%20said%20',.%20
Text:  Wendy said 'tea first' quickly, and Michael pressed her hand in gratitude, but the braver John hesitated.
Audio: WENDY SAID TEA FIRST QUICKLY AND MICHAEL PRESSED HER HAND IN GRATITUDE BUT THE BRAVER HESITATED

#:~:text='what%20kind%20of%20ad,%3F
Text:  'What kind of adventure?
Audio: WHAT KIND OF ADVENTURE

#:~:text='%20he%20asked%20,%20
Text:  ' he asked cautiously.
Audio: HE ASKED CAUTIOUSLY

#:~:text='there's%20a,.%20
Text:  'There's a pirate asleep in the pampas just beneath us,' Peter told him. 
Audio: THERE'S A PIROTE ASLEEP IN THE PAMPAS JUST BENEATH US PETER TOLD HIM

#:~:text='if%20you%20like%2C%20,.
Text:  'If you like, we'll go down and kill him.
