#:~:text='you%20as,.%20
Text:  'You ask him some questions,' he said to the others, wiping his damp brow.
Audio: You ask him some questions, he said to the others, wiping his damp brow.

#:~:text=smee%20r,%20
Text:  Smee reflected. 
Audio: Smee reflected.

#:~:text='i%20can't%20t,.%20
Text:  'I can't think of a thing,' he said regretfully.
Audio: I can't think of a thing, he said regretfully.

#:~:text='can',.%20
Text:  'Can't guess, can't guess,' crowed Peter. 
Audio: Can't guess, can't guess, crowed Peter.

#:~:text='do%20you%20g,%3F
Text:  'Do you give it up?
Audio: Do you give it up?

#:~:text=up%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=of%20course%20in,.%20
Text:  Of course in his pride he was carrying the game too far, and the miscreants saw their chance.
Audio: Of course, in his pride, he was carrying the game too far, and the miscreants saw their chance.

#:~:text='yes%2C%20y,.%20
Text:  'Yes, yes,' they answered eagerly.
Audio: Yes, yes, they answered eagerly.

#:~:text='well%2C%20t,.
Text:  'Well, then,' he cried, 'I am Peter Pan.
Audio: Well then, he cried, I am Peter Pan.

#:~:text=pan.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=pan!
Text:  Pan!
Audio: Pan.

#:~:text=in%20a%20mom,.%20
Text:  In a moment Hook was himself again, and Smee and Starkey were his faithful henchmen.
Audio: In a moment, Hook was himself again, and Smee and Starkey were his faithful henchmen.

#:~:text='now%20w,.%20
Text:  'Now we have him,' Hook shouted. 
Audio: Now we have him, Hook shouted.

#:~:text='in,.%20
Text:  'Into the water, Smee. 
Audio: Into the water, Smee.

#:~:text=starkey%2C%20m,.%20
Text:  Starkey, mind the boat. 
Audio: Starkey, mind the boat.

#:~:text=take%20him%20d,.
Text:  Take him dead or alive.
Audio: Take him, dead or alive.

#:~:text=ve.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=he%20leape,.%20
Text:  He leaped as he spoke, and simultaneously came the gay voice of Peter.
Audio: He leaped as he spoke, and simultaneously came the gay voice of Peter.

#:~:text='are%20you%20ready%2C%20b,%3F
Text:  'Are you ready, boys?
Audio: Are you ready, boys?

#:~:text=%2C%20boys%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='ay%2C%20ay%2C'%20f,.%20
Text:  'Ay, ay,' from various parts of the lagoon.
Audio: Aye, aye, from various parts of the lagoon.

#:~:text='then%20la,.
Text:  'Then lam into the pirates.
Audio: Then lay him into the pirates!

#:~:text=ates.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=the%20fight%20w,.%20
Text:  The fight was short and sharp. 
Audio: The fight was short and sharp.

#:~:text=first%20to%20d,.%20
Text:  First to draw blood was John, who gallantly climbed into the boat and held Starkey. 
Audio: First to draw blood was John, who gallantly climbed into the boat and held Starkey.

#:~:text=there%20was%20a%20fie,.%20
Text:  There was a fierce struggle, in which the cutlass was torn from the pirate's grasp. 
Audio: There was fierce struggle, in which the cutlass was torn from the pirate's grasp.

#:~:text=he%20wri,.%20
Text:  He wriggled overboard and John leapt after him. 
Audio: He wriggled overboard, and John left after him.

#:~:text=the%20dinghy%20d,.%20
Text:  The dinghy drifted away.
Audio: The dinghy drifted away.

#:~:text=here%20and%20t,.%20
Text:  Here and there a head bobbed up in the water, and there was a flash of steel followed by a cry or a whoop. 
Audio: Here and there, a head bopped up in the water, and there was a flash of steel, followed by a cry or a whoop.

#:~:text=in%20the%20con,.%20
Text:  In the confusion some struck at their own side. 
Audio: In the confusion, some struck at their own side.

#:~:text=the%20cork,.%20
Text:  The corkscrew of Smee got Tootles in the fourth rib, but he was himself pinked in turn by Curly. 
Audio: The corkscrew of Smee got Tootles in the fourth rib, but he was himself pinked and turned by Curly.

#:~:text=fart,.%20
Text:  Farther from the rock Starkey was pressing Slightly and the twins hard.
Audio: Further up the rock, Starkey was pressing slightly in the twins, hard.

#:~:text=where%20all%20t,%3F%20
Text:  Where all this time was Peter? 
Audio: Where, all this time, was Peter?

#:~:text=he%20was%20se,.%20
Text:  He was seeking bigger game.
Audio: He was seeking bigger game.

#:~:text=the%20others%20were%20a,.%20
Text:  The others were all brave boys, and they must not be blamed for backing from the pirate captain. 
Audio: The others were all brave boys, and they must not be blamed for backing from the pirate captain.

#:~:text=his%20iron%20claw%20m,.%20
Text:  His iron claw made a circle of dead water round him, from which they fled like affrighted fishes.
Audio: His iron claw made a circle of dead water round him, from which they fled like affrighted fishes.

#:~:text=but%20there%20was%20one%20w,.%20
Text:  But there was one who did not fear him: there was one prepared to enter that circle.
Audio: But there was one who did not fear him. There was one prepared to enter that circle.

#:~:text=strangely%2C,.%20
Text:  Strangely, it was not in the water that they met. 
Audio: Strangely, it was not in the water that they met.

#:~:text=hook%20ros,.%20
Text:  Hook rose to the rock to breathe, and at the same moment Peter scaled it on the opposite side. 
Audio: Hook rose to the rock to breathe, and at the same moment, Peter scaled it on the opposite side.

#:~:text=the%20rock%20was%20s,.%20
Text:  The rock was slippery as a ball, and they had to crawl rather than climb. 
Audio: The rock was slippery as a ball, and they had to crawl rather than climb.

#:~:text=neither%20k,.%20
Text:  Neither knew that the other was coming. 
Audio: Neither knew that the other was coming.

#:~:text=each%20f,.%20
Text:  Each feeling for a grip met the other's arm: in surprise they raised their heads; their faces were almost touching; so they met.
Audio: Each, feeling for a grip, met the other's arm. In surprise, they raised their heads. Their faces were almost touching. So they met.

#:~:text=some%20of%20the%20,.%20
Text:  Some of the greatest heroes have confessed that just before they fell to they had a sinking. 
Audio: Some of the greatest heroes have confessed that just before they fell to, they had a sinking.

#:~:text=had%20i,.%20
Text:  Had it been so with Peter at that moment I would admit it. 
Audio: Had it been so with Peter at that moment, I would admit it.

#:~:text=after%20all%2C%20thi,.%20
Text:  After all, this was the only man that the Sea-Cook had feared. 
Audio: After all, he was the only man that the sea-cook had feared.

#:~:text=but%20peter%20h,.%20
Text:  But Peter had no sinking, he had one feeling only, gladness; and he gnashed his pretty teeth with joy. 
Audio: But Peter had no sinking. He had one feeling only, gladness. And he gnashed his pretty teeth with joy.

#:~:text=quick%20a,.%20
Text:  Quick as thought he snatched a knife from Hook's belt and was about to drive it home, when he saw that he was higher up the rock than his foe. 
Audio: Quick as thought, he snatched a knife from Hook's belt, and was about to drive it home when he saw that he was higher up the rock than his foe.

#:~:text=it%20would%20n,.%20
Text:  It would not have been fighting fair. 
Audio: It would not have been fighting fair.

#:~:text=he%20gave%20t,.%20
Text:  He gave the pirate a hand to help him up.
Audio: He gave the pirate a hand to help him up.

#:~:text=it%20was%20then%20,.%20
Text:  It was then that Hook bit him.
Audio: It was then that Hook bit him.

#:~:text=not%20the%20p,.%20
Text:  Not the pain of this but its unfairness was what dazed Peter. 
Audio: Not the pain of this, but its unfairness was what dazed Peter.

#:~:text=it%20made%20him,.%20
Text:  It made him quite helpless. 
Audio: It made him quite helpless.

#:~:text=he%20could%20o,.%20
Text:  He could only stare, horrified. 
Audio: He could only stare, horrified.

#:~:text=every%20c,.%20
Text:  Every child is affected thus the first time he is treated unfairly. 
Audio: Every child is affected thus the first time he is treated unfairly.

#:~:text=all%20he%20t,.%20
Text:  All he thinks he has a right to when he comes to you to be yours is fairness. 
Audio: All he thinks he has a right to when he comes to you to be yours is fairness.

#:~:text=after%20you%20,.%20
Text:  After you have been unfair to him he will love you again, but he will never afterwards be quite the same boy. 
Audio: After you have been unfair to him, he will love you again, but will never afterwards be quite the same boy.

#:~:text=no%20one%20ev,.%20
Text:  No one ever gets over the first unfairness; no one except Peter. 
Audio: No one ever gets over the first unfairness. No one except Peter.

#:~:text=he%20often%20m,.%20
Text:  He often met it, but he always forgot it. 
Audio: He often met it, but he always forgot it.

#:~:text=i%20suppose%20t,.%20
Text:  I suppose that was the real difference between him and all the rest.
Audio: I suppose that was the real difference between him and all the rest.

#:~:text=so%20wh,.%20
Text:  So when he met it now it was like the first time; and he could just stare, helpless. 
Audio: So when he met it now, it was like the first time. And he could just stare, helpless.

#:~:text=twice%20t,.%20
Text:  Twice the iron hand clawed him.
Audio: Twice the iron hand clawed him.

#:~:text=a%20few%20minutes%20a,.%20
Text:  A few minutes afterwards the other boys saw Hook in the water striking wildly for the ship; no elation on his pestilent face now, only white fear, for the crocodile was in dogged pursuit of him. 
Audio: A few moments afterwards, the other boys saw Hook in the water striking wildly for the ship. No elation on the pestilent face now, only white fear, for the crocodile was in dogged pursuit of him.

#:~:text=on%20or,.%20
Text:  On ordinary occasions the boys would have swum alongside cheering; but now they were uneasy, for they had lost both Peter and Wendy, and were scouring the lagoon for them, calling them by name. 
Audio: On ordinary occasions, the boys would have swum alongside cheering, but now they were uneasy, for they had lost both Peter and Wendy, and were scouring the lagoon for them, calling them by name.

#:~:text=they%20found%20t,.%20
Text:  They found the dinghy and went home in it, shouting 'Peter, Wendy' as they went, but no answer came save mocking laughter from the mermaids. 
Audio: They found the dinghy and went home in it, shouting, Peter, Wendy, as they went, but no answer came, save mocking laughter from the mermaids.

#:~:text='they%20m,.%20
Text:  'They must be swimming back or flying,' the boys concluded. 
Audio: They must be swimming back or flying, the boys concluded.

#:~:text=they%20were%20not%20v,.%20
Text:  They were not very anxious, they had such faith in Peter. 
Audio: They were not very anxious, because they had such faith in Peter.

#:~:text=they%20ch,!%20
Text:  They chuckled, boylike, because they would be late for bed; and it was all mother Wendy's fault!
Audio: They chuckled, boy-like, because they would be late for bed, and it was all Mother Wendy's fault.

#:~:text=when%20thei,.%20
Text:  When their voices died away there came cold silence over the lagoon, and then a feeble cry.
Audio: When their voices died away, there came cold silence over the lagoon, and then a feeble cry.

#:~:text='hel,!
Text:  'Help, help!
Audio: Help! Help!

#:~:text=lp!-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=two%20sm,.%20
Text:  Two small figures were beating against the rock; the girl had fainted and lay on the boy's arm. 
Audio: Two small figures were beating against the rock. The girl had fainted and lay on the boy's arm.

#:~:text=with%20a%20la,.%20
Text:  With a last effort Peter pulled her up the rock and then lay down beside her. 
Audio: With a last effort, Peter pulled her up the rock and then lay down beside her. Even as he

#:~:text=even%20as,.%20
Text:  Even as he also fainted he saw that the water was rising. 
Audio: Even as he also fainted, he saw that the water was rising.

#:~:text=he%20knew%20that%20they,.%20
Text:  He knew that they would soon be drowned, but he could do no more.
Audio: He knew that they would soon be drowned, but he could do no more.

#:~:text=as%20they%20l,.%20
Text:  As they lay side by side a mermaid caught Wendy by the feet, and began pulling her softly into the water. 
Audio: As they lay side by side, a mermaid caught Wendy by the feet and began pulling her softly into the water.

#:~:text=peter%2C%20f,.%20
Text:  Peter, feeling her slip from him, woke with a start, and was just in time to draw her back. 
Audio: Peter, feeling her slip from him, woke with a start and was just in time to draw her back.

#:~:text=but%20he%20had%20t,.%20
Text:  But he had to tell her the truth.
Audio: But he had to tell her the truth.

#:~:text='we%20are%20o,.%20
Text:  'We are on the rock, Wendy,' he said, 'but it is growing smaller. 
Audio: We're on the rock, Wendy, he said. But it is growing smaller.

#:~:text=soon%20t,.
Text:  Soon the water will be over it.
Audio: Soon the water will be over it.

#:~:text=%20it.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=she%20did%20not%20u,.%20
Text:  She did not understand even now.
Audio: She did not understand even now.

#:~:text='we%20must%20g,.%20
Text:  'We must go,' she said, almost brightly.
Audio: We must go, she said, almost brightly.

#:~:text='yes%2C'%20h,.%20
Text:  'Yes,' he answered faintly.
Audio: Yes, he answered faintly.

#:~:text='shall%20we%20sw,%3F
Text:  'Shall we swim or fly, Peter?
Audio: Shall we swim or fly, Peter?

#:~:text=ter%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=he%20had%20to%20tell%20her.
Text:  He had to tell her.
Audio: He had to tell her.

#:~:text='do%20you%20think%20y,%3F
Text:  'Do you think you could swim or fly as far as the island, Wendy, without my help?
Audio: Do you think you could swim or fly as far as the island, Wendy, without my help?

#:~:text=lp%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=she%20had%20to%20a,.%20
Text:  She had to admit that she was too tired.
Audio: She had to admit that she was too tired.

#:~:text=he%20moa,%20
Text:  He moaned.
Audio: He moaned.

#:~:text=ed.%20-,'what%20is%20it%3F
Text:  'What is it?
Audio: What is it?

#:~:text='%20she%20asked%2C%20a,.%20
Text:  ' she asked, anxious about him at once.
Audio: She asked, anxious about him at once.

#:~:text='i%20can't%20h,.%20
Text:  'I can't help you, Wendy. 
Audio: I can't help you, Wendy.

#:~:text=hook%20woun,.%20
Text:  Hook wounded me. 
Audio: Hook wounded me.

#:~:text=i%20can%20n,.
Text:  I can neither fly nor swim.
Audio: I can neither fly nor swim.

#:~:text=swim.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='do%20you%20m,%3F
Text:  'Do you mean we shall both be drowned?
Audio: Do you mean we shall both be drowned?

#:~:text=ed%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='loo,.
Text:  'Look how the water is rising.
Audio: Look how the water's rising.

#:~:text=ng.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=they%20put%20t,.%20
Text:  They put their hands over their eyes to shut out the sight. 
Audio: They put their hands over their eyes to shut out the sight.

#:~:text=they%20thought%20the,.%20
Text:  They thought they would soon be no more. 
Audio: They thought they would soon be no more.

#:~:text=as%20they%20sat,%3F
Text:  As they sat thus something brushed against Peter as light as a kiss, and stayed there, as if saying timidly, 'Can I be of any use?
Audio: As they sat thus, something brushed against Peter, as light as a kiss, and stayed there, as if saying timidly, Can I be of any use?

#:~:text=se%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=it%20was%20the%20ta,.%20
Text:  It was the tail of a kite, which Michael had made some days before. 
Audio: It was the tail of a kite, which Michael had made some days before.

#:~:text=it%20had%20tor,.%20
Text:  It had torn itself out of his hand and floated away.
Audio: It had torn itself out of his hand and floated away.

#:~:text='michael',.%20
Text:  'Michael's kite,' Peter said without interest, but next moment he had seized the tail, and was pulling the kite toward him.
Audio: Michael's kite, Peter said without interest. But next moment he had seized the tail and was pulling the kite toward him.

#:~:text='it%20l,%3F
Text:  'It lifted Michael off the ground,' he cried; 'why should it not carry you?
Audio: It lifted Michael off the ground, he cried. Why should it not carry you?

#:~:text=ou%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='bot,!
Text:  'Both of us!
Audio: Both of us.

#:~:text=us!-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='it%20ca,.
Text:  'It can't lift two; Michael and Curly tried.
Audio: I can't lift two, Michael and Curly tried.

#:~:text=ied.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='let%20us%20d,.%20
Text:  'Let us draw lots,' Wendy said bravely.
Audio: Let us draw lots, Wendy said bravely.

#:~:text='and%20you%20a%20,.
Text:  'And you a lady; never.
Audio: And you a lady? Never. Already he had

#:~:text='%20al,.%20
Text:  ' Already he had tied the tail round her. 
Audio: Already he had tied the tail round her.

#:~:text=she%20cl,.%20
Text:  She clung to him; she refused to go without him; but with a 'Good-bye, Wendy,' he pushed her from the rock; and in a few minutes she was borne out of his sight. 
Audio: She clung to him. She refused to go without him. But with a good-bye, Wendy, he pushed her from the rock, and in a few minutes she was borne out of his sight.

#:~:text=peter%20was%20a,.%20
Text:  Peter was alone on the lagoon.
Audio: Peter was alone on the lagoon.

#:~:text=the%20rock%20was%20v,.%20
Text:  The rock was very small now; soon it would be submerged. 
Audio: The rock was very small now. Soon it would be submerged.

#:~:text=pale%20r,.%20
Text:  Pale rays of light tiptoed across the waters; and by and by there was to be heard a sound at once the most musical and the most melancholy in the world: the mermaids calling to the moon.
Audio: Pale rays of light tiptoed across the waters, and by and by there was to be heard a sound at once the most musical and the most melancholy in the world. The mermaids calling to the moon.

#:~:text=peter%20was%20not%20q,.%20
Text:  Peter was not quite like other boys; but he was afraid at last. 
Audio: Peter was not quite like other boys, but he was afraid at last.

#:~:text=a%20trem,.%20
Text:  A tremor ran through him, like a shudder passing over the sea; but on the sea one shudder follows another till there are hundreds of them, and Peter felt just the one. 
Audio: A tremor ran through him, like a shudder passing over the sea. But on the sea one shudder follows another until there are hundreds of them, and Peter felt just the one.

#:~:text=next%20moment%20he%20w,.%20
Text:  Next moment he was standing erect on the rock again, with that smile on his face and a drum beating within him. 
Audio: Next moment he was standing erect on the rock again, with that smile on his face and a drum beating within him.

#:~:text=it%20was%20sa,.
Text:  It was saying, 'To die will be an awfully big adventure.
Audio: It was saying, to die will be an awfully big adventure. End of chapter 8 Thank you. Thank you. Thank you. Thank you. Thank you.

#:~:text=ure.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: CHAPTER

#:~:text=chapter%20i
Text:  CHAPTER IX
Audio: IX.

#:~:text=x%20-,the%20never%20bird%20
Text:  THE NEVER BIRD
Audio: THE NEVER-BIRD

#:~:text=the%20last%20s,.%20
Text:  The last sounds Peter heard before he was quite alone were the mermaids retiring one by one to their bedchambers under the sea. 
Audio: The last sound Peter heard before he was quite alone were the mermaids retiring one by one to their bedchambers under the sea.

#:~:text=he%20was%20too%20far,.%20
Text:  He was too far away to hear their doors shut; but every door in the coral caves where they live rings a tiny bell when it opens or closes (as in all the nicest houses on the mainland), and he heard the bells.
Audio: He was too far away to hear their doors shut, but every door in the coral caves where they live rings a tiny bell when it opens or closes, as in all the nicest houses on the mainland, and he heard the bells.

#:~:text=steadily%20t,.%20
Text:  Steadily the waters rose till they were nibbling at his feet; and to pass the time until they made their final gulp, he watched the only thing moving on the lagoon. 
Audio: As he was standing at his feet, and to pass the time until they made their final gulp, he watched the only thing on the lagoon. He

#:~:text=he%20thought%20i,.%20
Text:  He thought it was a piece of floating paper, perhaps part of the kite, and wondered idly how long it would take to drift ashore.
Audio: thought it was a piece of floating paper, perhaps part of the kite, and wondered idly how long it would take to drift ashore. Presently

#:~:text=presently%20he,.%20
Text:  Presently he noticed as an odd thing that it was undoubtedly out upon the lagoon with some definite purpose, for it was fighting the tide, and sometimes winning; and when it won, Peter, always sympathetic to the weaker side, could not help clapping; it was such a gallant piece of paper.
Audio: he noticed, as an odd thing, that it was undoubtedly out upon the lagoon with some definite purpose, for it was fighting the tide, and sometimes winning. And when it won, Peter, always sympathetic to the weaker side, could not help clapping. It was such a gallant piece of paper. It

#:~:text=it%20was%20not%20really%20a,.%20
Text:  It was not really a piece of paper; it was the Never bird, making desperate efforts to reach Peter on her nest. 
Audio: was not really a piece of paper. It was the never-bird, making desperate efforts to reach Peter on the nest.

#:~:text=by%20wo,.%20
Text:  By working her wings, in a way she had learned since the nest fell into the water, she was able to some extent to guide her strange craft, but by the time Peter recognised her she was very exhausted. 
Audio: By working her wings in a way she had learned since the nest fell into the water, she was able to some extent to guide her strange craft. But by the time Peter recognized her, she was very exhausted.

#:~:text=she%20had%20come%20to%20s,.%20
Text:  She had come to save him, to give him her nest, though there were eggs in it. 
Audio: She had come to save him, to give him her nest, though there were eggs in it.

#:~:text=i%20ra,.%20
Text:  I rather wonder at the bird, for though he had been nice to her, he had also sometimes tormented her. 
Audio: I rather wonder at the bird, for though he had been nice to her, he had also sometimes tormented her.

#:~:text=i%20can%20s,h.%20
Text:  I can suppose only that, like Mrs. Darling and the rest of them, she was melted because he had all his first teeth.
Audio: I can suppose only that, like Mrs. Darling and the rest of them, she was melted because he had all his first teeth.

#:~:text=she%20cal,.%20
Text:  She called out to him what she had come for, and he called out to her what was she doing there; but of course neither of them understood the other's language. 
Audio: She called out to him what she had come for, and he called out to her what she was doing there. But, of course, neither of them understood the other's language.

#:~:text=in%20fan,.%20
Text:  In fanciful stories people can talk to the birds freely, and I wish for the moment I could pretend that this was such a story, and say that Peter replied intelligently to the Never bird; but truth is best, and I want to tell only what really happened. 
Audio: In fanciful stories, people can talk to the birds freely, and I wish for the moment I could pretend that this were such a story, and say that Peter replied intelligently to the never-bird. But truth is best, and I want to tell you only what really happened.

#:~:text=well%2C%20n,.%20
Text:  Well, not only could they not understand each other, but they forgot their manners.
Audio: Well, not only could they not understand each other, but they forgot their manners.

#:~:text='i%E2%80%94want%E2%80%94you%E2%80%94t,.
Text:  'I—want—you—to—get—into—the—nest,' the bird called, speaking as slowly and distinctly as possible, 'and—then—you—can—drift—ashore, but—I—am—too—tired—to—bring—it—any—nearer—so—you—must—try—to—swim—to—it.
Audio: I want you to get into the nest. I want you to get into the nest, the bird called, speaking as slowly and distinctly as possible. And then you can drift ashore. But I am too tired to bring it any nearer, so you must try to swim to it.

#:~:text=%E2%80%94it.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='what%20are%20you%20,%3F
Text:  'What are you quacking about?
Audio: What are you quacking about?

#:~:text='%20peter%20a,%20
Text:  ' Peter answered. 
Audio: Peter answered.

#:~:text='why%20don't%20you%20l,%3F
Text:  'Why don't you let the nest drift as usual?
Audio: Why don't you let the nest drift as usual?

#:~:text=al%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='i%E2%80%94want%E2%80%94you%E2%80%94',.%20
Text:  'I—want—you—' the bird said, and repeated it all over.
Audio: I want you, the bird said, and repeated it all over.

#:~:text=then%20peter%20t,.%20
Text:  Then Peter tried slow and distinct.
Audio: Then Peter tried slow and distinct.

#:~:text='what%E2%80%94,%3F
Text:  'What—are—you—quacking—about?
Audio: What are you quacking about?

#:~:text='%20and%20so%20on.
Text:  ' and so on.
Audio: And so on.

#:~:text=the%20never%20bird%20b,.%20
Text:  The Never bird became irritated; they have very short tempers.
Audio: The never-bird became irritated. They have very short tempers.

#:~:text='you%20d,%3F
Text:  'You dunderheaded little jay,' she screamed, 'why don't you do as I tell you?
Audio: 

#:~:text=ou%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: dunder-headed little jay! she screamed. Why don't you do as I tell you?

#:~:text=peter%20felt%20t,%3A%20
Text:  Peter felt that she was calling him names, and at a venture he retorted hotly:
Audio: Peter felt that she was calling him names, and at a venture he retorted hotly,

#:~:text='so%20,!
Text:  'So are you!
Audio: 

#:~:text=u!-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: are you!

#:~:text=then%20r,%3A%20
Text:  Then rather curiously they both snapped out the same remark:
Audio: Then, rather curiously, they both snapped out the same remark.

#:~:text=%3A%20-,'shut%20up!
Text:  'Shut up!
Audio: 

#:~:text=up!-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: up!

#:~:text='%20-,'shut%20up!
Text:  'Shut up!
Audio: 

#:~:text=up!-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: up!

#:~:text=nevertheless%20t,.%20
Text:  Nevertheless the bird was determined to save him if she could, and by one last mighty effort she propelled the nest against the rock. 
Audio: Nevertheless, the bird was determined to save him if she could. And by one last mighty effort, she propelled the nest against the rock.

#:~:text=then%20u,.%20
Text:  Then up she flew; deserting her eggs, so as to make her meaning clear.
Audio: Then up she flew, deserting her eggs so as to make her meaning clear.

#:~:text=then%20at%20last%20he%20u,.%20
Text:  Then at last he understood, and clutched the nest and waved his thanks to the bird as she fluttered overhead. 
Audio: Then at last he understood, and clutched the nest and waved his thanks to the bird as she fluttered overhead.

#:~:text=it%20was%20not%20to,.%20
Text:  It was not to receive his thanks, however, that she hung there in the sky; it was not even to watch him get into the nest; it was to see what he did with her eggs.
Audio: It was not to receive his thanks, however, that she hung there in the sky. It was not even to watch him get into the nest. It was to see what he did with her eggs.

#:~:text=there%20were%20t,.%20
Text:  There were two large white eggs, and Peter lifted them up and reflected. 
Audio: There were two large white eggs, and Peter lifted them up and reflected.

#:~:text=the%20bird%20co,.%20
Text:  The bird covered her face with her wings, so as not to see the last of her eggs; but she could not help peeping between the feathers.
Audio: The bird covered her face with her wings so as not to see the last of them. But she could not help peeping between the feathers.

#:~:text=i%20fo,.%20
Text:  I forget whether I have told you that there was a stave on the rock, driven into it by some buccaneers of long ago to mark the site of buried treasure. 
Audio: I forgot whether I have told you that there was a stave on the rock, driven into it by some buccaneers of long ago to mark the site of buried treasure.

#:~:text=the%20children%20had%20d,.%20
Text:  The children had discovered the glittering hoard, and when in mischievous mood used to fling showers of moidores, diamonds, pearls and pieces of eight to the gulls, who pounced upon them for food, and then flew away, raging at the scurvy trick that had been played upon them. 
Audio: The children had discovered the glittering hoard, and when in a mischievous mood used to fling showers of moidors, diamonds, pearls, and pieces of eight to the gulls, who pounced upon them for food, and then flew away, raging at the scurvy trick that had been played upon them.

#:~:text=the%20stave%20w,.%20
Text:  The stave was still there, and on it Starkey had hung his hat, a deep tarpaulin, watertight, with a broad brim. 
Audio: The stave was still there, and on it Starkey had hung his hat, a deep tarpaulin, water-tight with a broad brim.

#:~:text=peter%20put,.%20
Text:  Peter put the eggs into this hat and set it on the lagoon. 
Audio: Peter put the eggs into this hat and set it on the lagoon.

#:~:text=it%20floa,.%20
Text:  It floated beautifully.
Audio: It floated beautifully.

#:~:text=the%20never%20bird%20s,.%20
Text:  The Never bird saw at once what he was up to, and screamed her admiration of him; and, alas, Peter crowed his agreement with her. 
Audio: The never-bird saw at once what he was up to, and screamed her admiration of him. And alas, Peter crowed his agreement with her.

#:~:text=then%20he%20g,.%20
Text:  Then he got into the nest, reared the stave in it as a mast, and hung up his shirt for a sail. 
Audio: Then he got into the nest, reared the stave in it as a mast, and hung up his shirt for a sail.

#:~:text=at%20the%20same%20moment%20t,.%20
Text:  At the same moment the bird fluttered down upon the hat and once more sat snugly on her eggs. 
Audio: At the same moment the bird fluttered down upon the hat, and once more sat snugly on her eggs.

#:~:text=she%20dr,.%20
Text:  She drifted in one direction, and he was borne off in another, both cheering.
Audio: She drifted in one direction, and he was borne off in another, both cheering.

#:~:text=of%20course%20wh,.%20
Text:  Of course when Peter landed he beached his barque in a place where the bird would easily find it; but the hat was such a great success that she abandoned the nest. 
Audio: Of course, when Peter landed, he beached his bark. Small ship. Actually, the never-bird's nest in this particular case in point. In a place where the bird would easily find it. But the hat was such a great success that she abandoned the nest.

#:~:text=it%20drif,.%20
Text:  It drifted about till it went to pieces, and often Starkey came to the shore of the lagoon, and with many bitter feelings watched the bird sitting on his hat. 
Audio: It drifted about till it went to pieces, and often Starkey came to the shore of the lagoon, and with many bitter feelings watched the bird sitting on his hat.

#:~:text=as%20we%20shall%20n,.%20
Text:  As we shall not see her again, it may be worth mentioning here that all Never birds now build in that shape of nest, with a broad brim on which the youngsters take an airing.
Audio: As we shall not see her again, it may be worth mentioning here that all never-birds now build in that shape of nest, with a broad brim on which the youngsters take an airing.

#:~:text=great%20we,.%20
Text:  Great were the rejoicings when Peter reached the home under the ground almost as soon as Wendy, who had been carried hither and thither by the kite. 
Audio: Great were the rejoicings when Peter reached the home under the ground almost as soon as Wendy, who had been carried hither and thither by the kite.

#:~:text=every%20boy%20,.%20
Text:  Every boy had adventures to tell; but perhaps the biggest adventure of all was that they were several hours late for bed. 
Audio: Every boy had adventures to tell, but perhaps the biggest adventure of all was that they were several hours late for bed.

#:~:text=this%20so,.%20
Text:  This so inflated them that they did various dodgy things to get staying up still longer, such as demanding bandages; but Wendy, though glorying in having them all home again safe and sound, was scandalised by the lateness of the hour, and cried, 'To bed, to bed,' in a voice that had to be obeyed. 
Audio: This so inflated them that they did various dodgy things to get staying up still longer, such as demanding bandages. But Wendy, though glorifying in having them all home again, safe and sound, was scandalized by the lateness of the hour, and cried, To bed, to bed, to bed, to bed, to bed, in a voice that had to be obeyed.

#:~:text=next%20day%2C,.%20
Text:  Next day, however, she was awfully tender, and gave out bandages to every one; and they played till bed-time at limping about and carrying their arms in slings.
Audio: Next day, however, she was awfully tender, and gave out bandages to every one, and they played till bed-time at limping about and carrying their arms in slings. End of chapter 9

#:~:text=chapter%20x%20
Text:  CHAPTER X
Audio: CHAPTER X.

#:~:text=the%20happy%20ho,%20
Text:  THE HAPPY HOME
Audio: THE HAPPY HOME

#:~:text=one%20im,.%20
Text:  One important result of the brush on the lagoon was that it made the redskins their friends. 
Audio: One important result of the brush on the lagoon was that it made the Redskins their friends.

#:~:text=peter%20had%20sa,.%20
Text:  Peter had saved Tiger Lily from a dreadful fate, and now there was nothing she and her braves would not do for him. 
Audio: Peter had saved Tiger Lily from a dreadful fate, and now there was nothing she and her braves would not do for him.

#:~:text=all%20ni,.%20
Text:  All night they sat above, keeping watch over the home under the ground and awaiting the big attack by the pirates which obviously could not be much longer delayed. 
Audio: All night they sat above, keeping watch over the home under the ground and awaiting the big attack by the pirates, which obviously could not be much longer delayed.

#:~:text=even%20by,.%20
Text:  Even by day they hung about, smoking the pipe of peace, and looking almost as if they wanted tit-bits to eat.
Audio: Even by day they hung about, smoking the pipe of peace and looking almost as if they wanted titbits to eat.

#:~:text=they%20called%20p,.%20
Text:  They called Peter the Great White Father, prostrating themselves before him; and he liked this tremendously, so that it was not really good for him.
Audio: They called Peter the Great White Father, prostrating themselves before him, and he liked this tremendously, so that it was not really good for him.

#:~:text='the%20gr,.
Text:  'The great white father,' he would say to them in a very lordly manner, as they grovelled at his feet, 'is glad to see the Piccaninny warriors protecting his wigwam from the pirates.
Audio: THE GREAT WHITE FATHER, HE WOULD SAY TO THEM IN A VERY LORDLY MANNER AS THEY GROVELED AT HIS FEET, IS GLAD TO SEE THE PIKANINNY WARRIORS PROTECTING HIS WIGWAM FROM THE PIRATES.

#:~:text=tes.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='me%20,.%20
Text:  'Me Tiger Lily,' that lovely creature would reply. 
Audio: ME TIGER LILLY, THAT LOVELY CREATURE WOULD REPLY,

#:~:text='peter%20pan%20s,.%20
Text:  'Peter Pan save me, me his velly nice friend. 
Audio: PETER PAN SAVE ME, ME HIS VELLY NICE FRIEND,

#:~:text=me%20n,.
Text:  Me no let pirates hurt him.
Audio: ME NO LET PIRATES HURT HIM.

#:~:text=him.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=she%20was%20far%20too%20p,.%20
Text:  She was far too pretty to cringe in this way, but Peter thought it his due, and he would answer condescendingly, 'It is good. 
Audio: SHE WAS FAR TOO PRETTY TO CRINGE IN THIS WAY. BUT PETER THOUGHT IT HIS DUE, AND HE WOULD ANSWER CONDESCENDINGLY, IT IS GOOD.

#:~:text=peter%20pan%20has%20spoken.
Text:  Peter Pan has spoken.
Audio: PETER PAN HAS SPOKEN.

#:~:text=ken.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=always%20wh,.%20
Text:  Always when he said, 'Peter Pan has spoken,' it meant that they must now shut up, and they accepted it humbly in that spirit; but they were by no means so respectful to the other boys, whom they looked upon as just ordinary braves. 
Audio: ALWAYS WHEN HE SAID, PETER PAN HAS SPOKEN, IT MEANT THAT THEY MUST NOW SHUT UP, AND THEY ACCEPTED IT HUMBLY IN THAT SPIRIT. BUT THEY WERE BY NO MEANS SO RESPECTFUL TO THE OTHER BOYS, WHOM THEY LOOKED UPON AS JUST ORDINARY BRAVES.

#:~:text=they%20said%20',%3F
Text:  They said 'How-do?
Audio: THEY SAID, HOW DO,

#:~:text='%20to%20,.%20
Text:  ' to them, and things like that; and what annoyed the boys was that Peter seemed to think this all right.
Audio: TO THEM, AND THINGS LIKE THAT. AND WHAT ANNOYED THE BOYS WAS THAT PETER SEEMED TO THINK THIS ALL RIGHT.

#:~:text=secretly%20we,.%20
Text:  Secretly Wendy sympathised with them a little, but she was far too loyal a housewife to listen to any complaints against father. 
Audio: SECRETLY WENDY SYMPATHIZED WITH THEM A LITTLE, BUT SHE WAS FAR TOO LOYAL A HOUSEWIFE TO LISTEN TO ANY COMPLAINTS AGAINST FATHER.

#:~:text='father%20,.%20
Text:  'Father knows best,' she always said, whatever her private opinion must be. 
Audio: FATHER KNOWS BEST, SHE ALWAYS SAID, WHATEVER HER PRIVATE OPINION MUST BE.

#:~:text=her%20private%20opinion%20w,.%20
Text:  Her private opinion was that the redskins should not call her a squaw.
Audio: HER PRIVATE OPINION WAS THAT THE RED SKINS SHOULD NOT CALL HER A SQUA.

#:~:text=we%20have%20now%20r,.%20
Text:  We have now reached the evening that was to be known among them as the Night of Nights, because of its adventures and their upshot. 
Audio: WE HAVE NOW REACHED THE EVENING THAT WAS TO BE NO ONE AMONG THEM AS THE NIGHT OF NIGHTS BECAUSE OF ITS ADVENTURES AND THEIR UPSHOT.

#:~:text=the%20day%2C,.%20
Text:  The day, as if quietly gathering its forces, had been almost uneventful, and now the redskins in their blankets were at their posts above, while, below, the children were having their evening meal; all except Peter, who had gone out to get the time. 
Audio: THE DAY, AS IF QUIETLY GATHERING ITS FORCES, HAD BEEN ALMOST UNEVENTFUL, AND NOW THE RED SKINS IN THEIR BLANKETS WERE AT THEIR POSTS ABOVE, WHILE BELOW THE CHILDREN WERE HAVING THEIR EVENING MEAL, ALL EXCEPT PETER, WHO HAD GONE OUT TO GET THE TIME.

#:~:text=the%20way%20y,.%20
Text:  The way you got the time on the island was to find the crocodile, and then stay near him till the clock struck.
Audio: THE WAY HE GOT THE TIME ON THE ISLAND WAS TO FIND THE CROCODY, AND THEN STAY NEAR HIM TILL THE CLOCK STRUCK.

#:~:text=this%20me,.%20
Text:  This meal happened to be a make-believe tea, and they sat round the board, guzzling in their greed; and really, what with their chatter and recriminations, the noise, as Wendy said, was positively deafening. 
Audio: THE MEAL HAPPENED TO BE A MAKE-BELIEVE TEA, AND THEY SAT AROUND THE BOARD GUZZLING IN THEIR GREED, AND REALLY, WHAT WITH THEIR CHATTER AND RECRIMINATIONS, THE NOISE, AS WENDY SAID, WAS POSITIVELY DEAFENING.

#:~:text=to%20be%20su,.%20
Text:  To be sure, she did not mind noise, but she simply would not have them grabbing things, and then excusing themselves by saying that Tootles had pushed their elbow. 
Audio: TO BE SURE, SHE DID NOT MIND NOISE, BUT SHE SIMPLY WOULD NOT HAVE THEM GRABBING THINGS AND THEN EXCUSING THEMSELVES BY SAYING THAT TOOTLES HAD PUSHED THEIR ELBOW.

#:~:text=there%20was%20a%20fix,.%20
Text:  There was a fixed rule that they must never hit back at meals, but should refer the matter of dispute to Wendy by raising the right arm politely and saying, 'I complain of so-and-so'; but what usually happened was that they forgot to do this or did it too much.
Audio: THERE WAS A FIXED RULE THAT THEY MUST NEVER HIT BACK AT MEALS, BUT SHOULD REFER THE MATTER OF DISPUTE TO WENDY BY RAISING THE RIGHT ARM POLITELY AND SAYING, I COMPLAIN OF SO-AND-SO. BUT WHAT USUALLY HAPPENED WAS THAT THEY FORGOT TO DO THIS, OR DID IT TOO MUCH.

#:~:text='silence%2C,.%20
Text:  'Silence,' cried Wendy when for the twentieth time she had told them that they were not all to speak at once. 
Audio: SILENCE, CRIED WENDY, WHEN FOR THE TWENTYTH TIME SHE HAD TOLD THEM THAT THEY WERE NOT ALL TO SPEAK AT ONCE.

#:~:text='is%20y,%3F
Text:  'Is your calabash empty, Slightly darling?
Audio: IS YOUR MUG EMPTY, SLIGHTLY DARLING?

#:~:text=ng%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='not%20q,.%20
Text:  'Not quite empty, mummy,' Slightly said, after looking into an imaginary mug.
Audio: NOT QUITE EMPTY, MUMMY, SLIGHTLY SAID, AFTER LOOKING INTO AN IMAGINARY MUG.

#:~:text='he%20h,.%20
Text:  'He hasn't even begun to drink his milk,' Nibs interposed.
Audio: HE HASN'T EVEN BEGUN TO DRINK HIS MILK, NIBS INTERPOSE.

#:~:text=this%20was%20te,.%20
Text:  This was telling, and Slightly seized his chance.
Audio: THIS WAS TELLING AND SLIGHTLY SEIZED HIS CHANCE.

#:~:text='i%20complain%20of%20nibs%2C,.%20
Text:  'I complain of Nibs,' he cried promptly.
Audio: I COMPLAIN OF NIBS, HE CRIED PROMPTLY.

#:~:text=john%2C%20h,.%20
Text:  John, however, had held up his hand first.
Audio: JOHN, HOWEVER, HAD HELD UP HIS HAND FIRST. WELL, JOHN,

#:~:text='well%2C%20j,%3F
Text:  'Well, John?
Audio: WELL, JOHN,

#:~:text=hn%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='may,%3F
Text:  'May I sit in Peter's chair, as he is not here?
Audio: MAY I SIT IN PETER'S CHAIR AS HE IS NOT HERE?

#:~:text=ere%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='sit,!
Text:  'Sit in father's chair, John!
Audio: SIT IN FATHER'S CHAIR, JOHN.

#:~:text='%20wendy%20w,.%20
Text:  ' Wendy was scandalised. 
Audio: WENDY WAS SCANDALIZED.

#:~:text='ce,.
Text:  'Certainly not.
Audio: CERTAINLY NOT.

#:~:text=ot.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='he%20i,.%20
Text:  'He is not really our father,' John answered. 
Audio: HE IS NOT REALLY OUR FATHER, JOHN ANSWERED.

#:~:text='he%20di,.
Text:  'He didn't even know how a father does till I showed him.
Audio: HE DIDN'T EVEN KNOW HOW A FATHER DOES TILL I SHOWED HIM.

#:~:text=im.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=this%20was%20g,%20
Text:  This was grumbling. 
Audio: THIS WAS GRUMBLING.

#:~:text='we%20c,.%20
Text:  'We complain of John,' cried the twins.
Audio: WE COMPLAIN OF JOHN, CRIED THE TWINS.

#:~:text=tootles%20he,.%20
Text:  Tootles held up his hand. 
Audio: TOOTLES HELD UP HIS HAND.

#:~:text=he%20was%20so%20m,.%20
Text:  He was so much the humblest of them, indeed he was the only humble one, that Wendy was specially gentle with him.
Audio: HE WAS SO MUCH THE HUMBLEST OF THEM, INDEED, HE WAS THE ONLY HUMBLE ONE, THAT WENDY WAS SPECIALLY GENTLE WITH HIM.

#:~:text='i%20don't%20suppose%2C',.
Text:  'I don't suppose,' Tootles said diffidently, 'that I could be father.
Audio: I DON'T SUPPOSE, TOOTLES SAID diffidently, THAT I COULD BE FATHER.

#:~:text=her.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='no%2C%20t,.
Text:  'No, Tootles.
Audio: NO, TOOTLES.

#:~:text=les.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=once%20to,.%20
Text:  Once Tootles began, which was not very often, he had a silly way of going on.
Audio: ONCE TOOTLES BEGAN, WHICH WAS NOT VERY OFTEN, HE HAD A SILLY WAY OF GOING ON.

#:~:text='as%20i%20can't%20be%20f,%3F
Text:  'As I can't be father,' he said heavily, 'I don't suppose, Michael, you would let me be baby?
Audio: AS I CAN'T BE FATHER, HE SAID HEAVILY. I DON'T SUPPOSE, MICHAEL, YOU WOULD LET ME BE BABY.

#:~:text=by%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='no%2C%20i%20,.%20
Text:  'No, I won't,' Michael rapped out. 
Audio: NO, I WON'T, MICHAEL WRAPPED OUT.

#:~:text=he%20was%20alr,.%20
Text:  He was already in his basket.
Audio: HE WAS ALREADY IN HIS BASKET.

#:~:text='as%20i%20can't%20be%20b,%3F
Text:  'As I can't be baby,' Tootles said, getting heavier and heavier, 'do you think I could be a twin?
Audio: AS I CAN'T BE BABY, TOOTLES SAID, GETTING HEAVIER AND HEAVIER AND HEAVIER. DO YOU THINK I COULD BE A TWIN?

#:~:text=in%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='no%2C%20indeed%2C',.
Text:  'No, indeed,' replied the twins; 'it's awfully difficult to be a twin.
Audio: NO, INDEED, REPUBLIED THE TWINS. IT'S AWFULLY DIFFICULT TO BE A TWIN.

#:~:text=win.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='as%20i%20can't%20be%20a,%3F
Text:  'As I can't be anything important,' said Tootles, 'would any of you like to see me do a trick?
Audio: AS I CAN'T BE ANYTHING IMPORTANT, SAID TOOTLES, WOULD ANY OF YOU LIKE TO SEE ME DO A TRICK?

#:~:text=ck%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='no%2C'%20t,.%20
Text:  'No,' they all replied.
Audio: NO, THEY ALL REPLIED.

#:~:text=then%20at%20last%20he%20st,%20
Text:  Then at last he stopped. 
Audio: THEN AT LAST HE STOPPED.

#:~:text='i%20hadn,.%20
Text:  'I hadn't really any hope,' he said.
Audio: I HADN'T REALLY ANY HOPE, HE SAID.

#:~:text=the%20hateful%20t,.%20
Text:  The hateful telling broke out again.
Audio: THE HATEFUL TELLING BROKE OUT AGAIN.

#:~:text='sl,.
