Audio: DEAR, OH, DEAR, CRIED WENDY. I'M SURE I SOMETIMES

#:~:text='oh%20dear%2C%20oh%20dear%2C'%20c,.
Text:  'Oh dear, oh dear,' cried Wendy, 'I'm sure I sometimes think that children are more trouble than they are worth.
Audio: THAT SPINSTERS ARE TO BE ENVIEED. SHE TOLD HIM TO

#:~:text=th.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: AWAY AND SAT DOWN TO HER WORK BASKET. A HEAVY LOAD OF

#:~:text=she%20told%20t,.%20
Text:  She told them to clear away, and sat down to her work-basket: a heavy load of stockings and every knee with a hole in it as usual.
Audio: AND EVERY KNEE WITH A HOLE IN IT AS USUAL. WENDY,

#:~:text='wendy%2C'%20r,.
Text:  'Wendy,' remonstrated Michael, 'I'm too big for a cradle.
Audio: MICHAEL, I'M TOO BIG FOR A CRADLE.

#:~:text=dle.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: MUST HAVE SOMEBODY IN A CRADLE, SHE SAID ALMOST

#:~:text='i%20m,.%20
Text:  'I must have somebody in a cradle,' she said almost tartly, 'and you are the littlest. 
Audio: AND YOU ARE THE LITTLEST. A CRADLE IS SUCH A NICE, HOMELY

#:~:text=a%20cradle%20,.
Text:  A cradle is such a nice homely thing to have about a house.
Audio: TO HAVE ABOUT A HOUSE. WHILE SHE SAWED THEY

#:~:text=use.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: AROUND HER. SUCH A GROUP OF HAPPY FACES

#:~:text=while%20she%20se,.%20
Text:  While she sewed they played around her; such a group of happy faces and dancing limbs lit up by that romantic fire. 
Audio: DANCING LIMBS LIT UP BY THAT ROMANTIC FIRE.

#:~:text=it%20had%20bec,.%20
Text:  It had become a very familiar scene this in the home under the ground, but we are looking on it for the last time.
Audio: IT HAD BECOME A VERY FAMILIAR SCENE, THIS, IN THE HOME UNDER THE GROUND.

#:~:text=there%20was%20a%20ste,.%20
Text:  There was a step above, and Wendy, you may be sure, was the first to recognise it.
Audio: BUT WE ARE LOOKING ON IT FOR THE LAST TIME.

#:~:text='ch,.%20
Text:  'Children, I hear your father's step. 
Audio: WAS A STEP ABOVE, AND WENDY,

#:~:text=he%20likes,.
Text:  He likes you to meet him at the door.
Audio: MAY BE SURE, WAS THE FIRST TO RECOGNIZE IT.

#:~:text=oor.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: I HEAR YOUR FATHER'S STEP. HE LIKED YOU TO MEET HIM AT THE DOOR.

#:~:text=above%2C%20t,.%20
Text:  Above, the redskins crouched before Peter.
Audio: THE RED SKINS CROUCHED BEFORE PETER. WATCH

#:~:text='wat,.%20
Text:  'Watch well, braves. 
Audio: WELL, BRAVES,

#:~:text=i%20have%20s,.
Text:  I have spoken.
Audio: I HAVE SPOKEN.

#:~:text=ken.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=and%20then%2C%20a,.%20
Text:  And then, as so often before, the gay children dragged him from his tree. 
Audio: AND THEN, AS SO OFTEN BEFORE, THE GAY CHILDREN DRAGGED HIM FROM HIS TREE.

#:~:text=as%20so%20often%20before%2C%20b,.%20
Text:  As so often before, but never again.
Audio: AS SO OFTEN BEFORE, BUT NEVER AGAIN.

#:~:text=he%20had%20brought%20n,.%20
Text:  He had brought nuts for the boys as well as the correct time for Wendy.
Audio: HE HAD BROUGHT NUTS FOR THE BOYS, AS WELL AS THE CORRECT TIME FOR WENDY.

#:~:text='peter%2C%20y,.%20
Text:  'Peter, you just spoil them, you know,' Wendy simpered.
Audio: PETER, YOU JUST SPOIL THEM, YOU KNOW, WENDY SIMPERED.

#:~:text='ah%2C%20old%20lady%2C'%20s,.%20
Text:  'Ah, old lady,' said Peter, hanging up his gun.
Audio: AH, OLD LADY, SAID PETER, HANGING UP HIS GUN.

#:~:text='it%20was%20m,.%20
Text:  'It was me told him mothers are called old lady,' Michael whispered to Curly.
Audio: IT WAS ME TOLD HIM MOTHERS ARE CALLED OLD LADY, MICHAEL WHISPERED TO CURLEY.

#:~:text='i%20complain%20of%20m,.%20
Text:  'I complain of Michael,' said Curly instantly.
Audio: I COMPLAIN OF MICHAEL, SAID CURLEY INSTANTLY.

#:~:text=the%20first%20twin%20c,.%20
Text:  The first twin came to Peter. 
Audio: THE FIRST TWIN CAME TO PETER.

#:~:text='father%2C,.
Text:  'Father, we want to dance.
Audio: FATHER, WE WANT TO DANCE.

#:~:text=ce.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='da,.%20
Text:  'Dance away, my little man,' said Peter, who was in high good humour.
Audio: DANCE AWAY, MY LITTLE MAN, SAID PETER, WHO WAS IN HIGH GOOD HUMOR.

#:~:text='but%20we,.
Text:  'But we want you to dance.
Audio: BUT WE WANT YOU TO DANCE.

#:~:text=ce.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=peter%20was%20r,.%20
Text:  Peter was really the best dancer among them, but he pretended to be scandalised.
Audio: PETER WAS REALLY THE BEST DANCER AMONG THEM, BUT HE PRETENDED TO BE SCANDALIZED.

#:~:text='me!
Text:  'Me! 
Audio: ME,

#:~:text=my%20o,.
Text:  My old bones would rattle.
Audio: MY OLD BONES WOULD RATTLE.

#:~:text=tle.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='and%20m,.
Text:  'And mummy too.
Audio: AND MOMMY, TOO.

#:~:text=too.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='what%2C,!
Text:  'What,' cried Wendy, 'the mother of such an armful, dance!
Audio: WHAT, CRIED WENDY, THE MOTHER OF SUCH AN ARMFUL DANCE.

#:~:text=ce!-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='but%20o,.%20
Text:  'But on a Saturday night,' Slightly insinuated.
Audio: BUT ON A SATURDAY NIGHT, SLIGHTLY INSINUATED.

#:~:text=it%20was%20not%20really%20s,.%20
Text:  It was not really Saturday night, at least it may have been, for they had long lost count of the days; but always if they wanted to do anything special they said this was Saturday night, and then they did it.
Audio: IT WAS NOT REALLY SATURDAY NIGHT, AT LEAST IT MAY HAVE BEEN, FOR THEY HAD LONG LOST COUNT OF THE DAYS. BUT ALWAYS IF THEY WANTED TO DO ANYTHING SPECIAL, THEY SAID THIS WAS SATURDAY NIGHT, AND THEN THEY DID IT.

#:~:text='of%20course%20it%20,.%20
Text:  'Of course it is Saturday night, Peter,' Wendy said, relenting.
Audio: OF COURSE IT IS SATURDAY NIGHT, PETER, WENDY SAID, RELENTING.

#:~:text='peo,.
Text:  'People of our figure, Wendy.
Audio: PEOPLE OF OUR FIGURE, WENDY.

#:~:text=dy.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='but%20it%20is%20o,.
Text:  'But it is only among our own progeny.
Audio: BUT IT IS ONLY AMONG OUR OWN PROGENY.

#:~:text=eny.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='tr,.
Text:  'True, true.
Audio: TRUE, TRUE.

#:~:text=ue.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=so%20they%20w,.%20
Text:  So they were told they could dance, but they must put on their nighties first.
Audio: SO THEY WERE TOLD THEY COULD DANCE, BUT THEY MUST PUT ON THEIR NIGHTIES FIRST.

#:~:text='ah%2C%20old%20lady%2C'%20p,.
Text:  'Ah, old lady,' Peter said aside to Wendy, warming himself by the fire and looking down at her as she sat turning a heel, 'there is nothing more pleasant, of an evening for you and me when the day's toil is over than to rest by the fire with the little ones near by.
Audio: AH, OLD LADY, PETER SAID ASIDE TO WENDY, WARMING HIMSELF BY THE FIRE AND LOOKING DOWN AT HER AS SHE SAT TURNING A HEEL. THERE IS NOTHING MORE PLEASANT OF AN EVENING FOR YOU AND ME WHEN THE DAY'S TOIL IS OVER THAN TO REST BY THE FIRE WITH THE LITTLE ONES NEARBY.

#:~:text=by.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='it%20is%20s,%3F
Text:  'It is sweet, Peter, isn't it?
Audio: IT IS SWEET PETER, ISN'T IT,

#:~:text='%20wendy%20said%2C%20f,.%20
Text:  ' Wendy said, frightfully gratified. 
Audio: WENDY SAID, FRIGHTFULLY GRATIFIED.

#:~:text='peter%2C%20i,.
Text:  'Peter, I think Curly has your nose.
Audio: PETER, I THINK CURLEY HAS YOUR NOSE.

#:~:text=ose.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='michael%20,.
Text:  'Michael takes after you.
Audio: MICHAEL TAKES AFTER YOU.

#:~:text=ou.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=she%20we,.%20
Text:  She went to him and put her hand on his shoulder.
Audio: SHE WENT TO HIM AND PUT HER HAND ON HIS SHOULDER.

#:~:text='dear%20p,%3F
Text:  'Dear Peter,' she said, 'with such a large family, of course, I have now passed my best, but you don't want to change me, do you?
Audio: DEAR PETER, SHE SAID, WITH SUCH A LARGE FAMILY, OF COURSE, I HAVE NOW PASSED MY BEST, BUT YOU DON'T WANT TO CHANGE ME, DO YOU?

#:~:text=ou%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='no%2C%20w,.
Text:  'No, Wendy.
Audio: NO, WENDY.

#:~:text=dy.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=certainly%20h,.%20
Text:  Certainly he did not want a change, but he looked at her uncomfortably; blinking, you know, like one not sure whether he was awake or asleep.
Audio: CERTAINLY HE DID NOT WANT TO CHANGE, BUT HE LOOKED AT HER UNCOMFORTABLY, BLINKING, YOU KNOW, LIKE ONE NOT SURE WHETHER HE WAS AWAKE OR ASLEEP.

#:~:text='peter%2C%20wh,%3F
Text:  'Peter, what is it?
Audio: PETER, WHAT IS IT?

#:~:text=it%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='i%20wa,.%20
Text:  'I was just thinking,' he said, a little scared. 
Audio: I WAS JUST THINKING, HE SAID, A LITTLE SCARED.

#:~:text='it%20is%20o,%3F
Text:  'It is only make-believe, isn't it, that I am their father?
Audio: IT IS ONLY MAKE-BELIEVE, ISN'T IT, THAT I AM THEIR FATHER?

#:~:text=her%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='oh%20yes%2C',.%20
Text:  'Oh yes,' Wendy said primly.
Audio: OH, YES, WENDY SAID, PRIMLY.

#:~:text='you%20see%2C'%20h,.
Text:  'You see,' he continued apologetically, 'it would make me seem so old to be their real father.
Audio: YOU SEE, HE CONTINUED APOLOGETICALLY, IT WOULD MAKE ME SEEM SO OLD TO BE THEIR REAL FATHER.

#:~:text=her.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='but%20t,.
Text:  'But they are ours, Peter, yours and mine.
Audio: BUT THEY ARE OURS, PETER, YOURS AND MINE.

#:~:text=mine.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='but%20n,%3F
Text:  'But not really, Wendy?
Audio: BUT NOT REALLY, WENDY,

#:~:text='%20he%20as,.%20
Text:  ' he asked anxiously.
Audio: HE ASKED ANXIOUSLY.

#:~:text='not%20i,.%20
Text:  'Not if you don't wish it,' she replied; and she distinctly heard his sigh of relief. 
Audio: NOT IF YOU DON'T WISH IT, SHE REPLIED. AND SHE DISTINCTLY HEARD HIS SIGH OF RELIEF.

#:~:text='peter%2C',%3F
Text:  'Peter,' she asked, trying to speak firmly, 'what are your exact feelings for me?
Audio: PETER, SHE ASKED, TRYING TO SPEAK FIRMLY. WHAT ARE YOUR EXACT FEELINGS TO ME?

#:~:text=%20me%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='those%20o,.
Text:  'Those of a devoted son, Wendy.
Audio: THOSE OF A DEVOTED SON, WENDY.

#:~:text=dy.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='i%20thought%20s,.%20
Text:  'I thought so,' she said, and went and sat by herself at the extreme end of the room.
Audio: I THOUGHT SO, SHE SAID, AND WENT AND SAT BY HERSELF AT THE EXTREME END OF THE ROOM.

#:~:text='you%20are%20s,.%20
Text:  'You are so queer,' he said, frankly puzzled, 'and Tiger Lily is just the same. 
Audio: YOU ARE SO QUEER, HE SAID, FRANKLY PUZZLED. AND TIGER LILLY IS JUST THE SAME.

#:~:text=there%20is%20s,.
Text:  There is something she wants to be to me, but she says it is not my mother.
Audio: THERE IS SOMETHING SHE WANTS TO BE TO ME, BUT SHE SAYS IT IS NOT MY MOTHER.

#:~:text=her.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='no%2C%20indeed%2C%20,.%20
Text:  'No, indeed, it is not,' Wendy replied with frightful emphasis. 
Audio: NO, INDEED IT IS NOT, WENDY REPLIED WITH FRIDFUL EMPHASIS.

#:~:text=now%20we%20k,.%20
Text:  Now we know why she was prejudiced against the redskins.
Audio: NOW WE KNOW WHY SHE WAS PREJUDICED AGAINST THE RED SKINS.

#:~:text='then%20what%20i,%3F
Text:  'Then what is it?
Audio: THEN WHAT IS IT?

#:~:text=it%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='it%20isn't%20f,.
Text:  'It isn't for a lady to tell.
Audio: IT ISN'T FOR A LADY TO TELL.

#:~:text=ll.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='oh%2C%20v,.%20
Text:  'Oh, very well,' Peter said, a little nettled. 
Audio: OH, VERY WELL, PETER SAID, A LITTLE NIDDLED.

#:~:text='perhaps%20tinke,.
Text:  'Perhaps Tinker Bell will tell me.
Audio: PERHAPS TINKER BELL WILL TELL ME.

#:~:text=%20me.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='oh%20yes%2C%20,.%20
Text:  'Oh yes, Tinker Bell will tell you,' Wendy retorted scornfully. 
Audio: OH, YES, TINKER BELL WILL TELL YOU, WENDY RETORTED SCORNFULLY.

#:~:text='she%20i,.
Text:  'She is an abandoned little creature.
Audio: SHE IS AN ABANDONED LITTLE CREATURE.

#:~:text=re.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=here%20ti,.%20
Text:  Here Tink, who was in her boudoir, eavesdropping, squeaked out something impudent.
Audio: HERE TINK, WHO WAS IN HER BEDROOM EATESTROPPING, SQUEAKED OUT SOMETHING IMPUDENT.

#:~:text='she%20says%20she%20g,.%20
Text:  'She says she glories in being abandoned,' Peter interpreted.
Audio: SHE SAYS SHE GLORIES IN BEING ABANDONED, PETER INTERPRETED.

#:~:text=he%20had%20a%20su,.%20
Text:  He had a sudden idea. 
Audio: HE HAD A SUDDEN IDEA.

#:~:text='perhaps%20tink%20,%3F
Text:  'Perhaps Tink wants to be my mother?
Audio: PERHAPS TINK WANTS TO BE MY MOTHER.

#:~:text=her%3F-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='you%20silly%20ass!
Text:  'You silly ass!
Audio: YOU SILLY ASS,

#:~:text='%20cried%20ti,.%20
Text:  ' cried Tinker Bell in a passion.
Audio: CRIED TINKER BELL IN A PASSION.

#:~:text=she%20had%20sa,.%20
Text:  She had said it so often that Wendy needed no translation.
Audio: SHE HAD SAID IT SO OFTEN THAT WENDY NEEDED NO TRANSLATION.

#:~:text='i%20al,.%20
Text:  'I almost agree with her,' Wendy snapped. 
Audio: I ALMOST AGREE WITH HER, WENDY SNAPPED.

#:~:text=fancy,.%20
Text:  Fancy Wendy snapping. 
Audio: FANCY WENDY SNAPPING.

#:~:text=but%20she%20ha,.%20
Text:  But she had been much tried, and she little knew what was to happen before the night was out. 
Audio: BUT SHE HAD BEEN MUCH TRIED, AND SHE LITTLE KNEW WHAT WAS TO HAPPEN BEFORE THE NIGHT WAS OUT.

#:~:text=if%20she%20had%20k,.%20
Text:  If she had known she would not have snapped.
Audio: IF SHE HAD KNOWN, SHE WOULD NOT HAVE SNAPPED.

#:~:text=none%20o,.%20
Text:  None of them knew. 
Audio: NONE OF THEM KNEW.

#:~:text=perhaps%20it%20w,.%20
Text:  Perhaps it was best not to know. 
Audio: PERHAPS IT WAS BEST NOT TO KNOW.

#:~:text=their%20i,.%20
Text:  Their ignorance gave them one more glad hour; and as it was to be their last hour on the island, let us rejoice that there were sixty glad minutes in it. 
Audio: THEIR IGNORANCE GAVE THEM ONE MORE GLAD HOUR. AND AS IT WAS TO BE THEIR LAST HOUR ON THE ISLAND, LET US REJOICE THAT THERE WERE SIXTY GLAD MINUTES IN IT.

#:~:text=they%20san,.%20
Text:  They sang and danced in their night-gowns. 
Audio: THEY SANG AND DANCED IN THEIR NIGHTGOWNS.

#:~:text=such%20a%20d,.%20
Text:  Such a deliciously creepy song it was, in which they pretended to be frightened at their own shadows; little witting that so soon shadows would close in upon them, from whom they would shrink in real fear. 
Audio: SUCH A DELICIOUSLY CREEPY SONG IT WAS, IN WHICH THEY PRETENDED TO BE FRIGHTENED AT THEIR OWN SHADOWS. LITTLE WEDDING THAT SO SOON SHADOWS WOULD CLOSE IN UPON THEM, FROM WHOM THEY WOULD SHRINK IN REAL FEAR.

#:~:text=so%20upr,!%20
Text:  So uproariously gay was the dance, and how they buffeted each other on the bed and out of it! 
Audio: SO UPROARIOUSLY GAY WAS THE DANCE, AND HOW THEY BUFFETED EACH OTHER ON THE BED AND OUT OF IT.

#:~:text=it%20was%20a%20pil,.%20
Text:  It was a pillow fight rather than a dance, and when it was finished, the pillows insisted on one bout more, like partners who know that they may never meet again. 
Audio: IT WAS A PILLOW FIGHT RATHER THAN A DANCE, AND WHEN IT WAS FINISHED THE PILLOWS INSISTED ON ONE BOUT MORE, LIKE PARTNERS WHO KNOW THAT THEY MAY NEVER MEET AGAIN.

#:~:text=the%20stories%20t,!%20
Text:  The stories they told, before it was time for Wendy's good-night story! 
Audio: THE STORIES THEY TOLD, BEFORE IT WAS TIME FOR WENDY'S GOOD NIGHT STORY.

#:~:text=even%20sl,%3A%20
Text:  Even Slightly tried to tell a story that night, but the beginning was so fearfully dull that it appalled even himself, and he said gloomily:
Audio: EVEN SLIGHTLY TRIED TO TELL A STORY THAT NIGHT, BUT THE BEGINNING WAS SO FEARFULLY DULL THAT IT APPALLED NOT ONLY THE OTHERS, BUT HIMSELF. AND HE SAID HAPPILY,

#:~:text='yes%2C%20i,.%20
Text:  'Yes, it is a dull beginning. 
Audio: YES, IT IS A DULL BEGINNING.

#:~:text=i%20sa,.
Text:  I say, let us pretend that it is the end.
Audio: I SAY, LET US PRETEND THAT IT IS THE END.

#:~:text=end.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text=and%20then%20at,.%20
Text:  And then at last they all got into bed for Wendy's story, the story they loved best, the story Peter hated. 
Audio: AND THEN AT LAST THEY ALL GOT INTO BED FOR WENDY'S STORY, THE STORY THEY LOVED BEST, THE STORY PETER HATED.

#:~:text=usually%20w,.%20
Text:  Usually when she began to tell this story he left the room or put his hands over his ears; and possibly if he had done either of those things this time they might all still be on the island. 
Audio: USUALLY WHEN SHE BEGAN TO TELL THIS STORY, HE LEFT THE ROOM OR PUT HIS HANDS OVER HIS EARS. AND POSSIBLY, IF HE HAD DONE EITHER OF THOSE THINGS THIS TIME, THEY MIGHT ALL STILL BE ON THE ISLAND.

#:~:text=but%20to-,.%20
Text:  Usually when she began to tell this story he left the room or put his hands over his ears; and possibly if he had done either of those things this time they might all still be on the island. 
Audio: BUT TONIGHT HE REMAINED ON HIS STOOL, AND WE SHALL SEE WHAT HAPPENED. END OF CHAPTER TEN

#:~:text=chapter%20xi%20
Text:  CHAPTER XI
Audio: CHAPTER XI.

#:~:text=wendy's%20story%20
Text:  WENDY'S STORY
Audio: WENDY'S STORY

#:~:text='lis,.%20
Text:  'Listen, then,' said Wendy, settling down to her story, with Michael at her feet and seven boys in the bed. 
Audio: Listen, then, said Wendy, settling down to her story, with Michael at her feet and seven boys in the bed.

#:~:text='there%20was%20o,'%20
Text:  'There was once a gentleman——'
Audio: There was once a gentleman.

#:~:text='i%20had%20,.%20
Text:  'I had rather he had been a lady,' Curly said.
Audio: I had rather he had been a lady, Curly said.

#:~:text='i%20wis,.%20
Text:  'I wish he had been a white rat,' said Nibs.
Audio: I wish he had been a white rat, said Nibs.

#:~:text='quiet%2C',.%20
