#:~:text=when%20wendy%20r,.%20
Text:  When Wendy returned diffidently she found Peter sitting on the bed-post crowing gloriously, while Jane in her nighty was flying round the room in solemn ecstasy.
Audio: When Wendy returned diffidently, she found Peter sitting on the bedpost crowing gloriously, while Jane in her nightie was flying round the room in solemn ecstasy.

#:~:text='she%20i,.%20
Text:  'She is my mother,' Peter explained; and Jane descended and stood by his side, with the look on her face that he liked to see on ladies when they gazed at him.
Audio: She's my mother, Peter explained, and Jane descended and stood by his side with a look on her face that he liked to see on ladies when they gazed at him.

#:~:text='he%20d,.%20
Text:  'He does so need a mother,' Jane said.
Audio: He does so need a mother, Jane said.

#:~:text='yes%2C%20i%20know%2C'%20w,'%20
Text:  'Yes, I know,' Wendy admitted rather forlornly; 'no one knows it so well as I.'
Audio: Yes, I know, Wendy admitted rather forlornly. No one knows it so well as I.

#:~:text='good-,.%20
Text:  'Yes, I know,' Wendy admitted rather forlornly; 'no one knows it so well as I.'
Audio: Good-bye, said Peter to Wendy, and he rose in the air, and the shameless Jane rose with him. It was already her easiest way of moving about.

#:~:text=wendy%20ru,.%20
Text:  Wendy rushed to the window.
Audio: Wendy rushed to the window.

#:~:text='no%2C%20no%2C'%20s,.%20
Text:  'No, no,' she cried.
Audio: No, no, she cried.

#:~:text='it%20is%20j,.
Text:  'It is just for spring-cleaning time,' Jane said; 'he wants me always to do his spring cleaning.
Audio: It is just for spring cleaning time, Jane said. He wants me always to do his spring cleaning.

#:~:text=ng.-,'%20
Text:  '
Audio: 

#:~:text='if,.%20
Text:  'If only I could go with you,' Wendy sighed.
Audio: If only I could go with you, Wendy sighed.

#:~:text='you%20see%20y,.%20
Text:  'You see you can't fly,' said Jane.
Audio: You see you can't fly, said Jane.

#:~:text=of%20course%20i,.%20
Text:  Of course in the end Wendy let them fly away together. 
Audio: Of course, in the end, Wendy let them fly away together.

#:~:text=our%20la,.%20
Text:  Our last glimpse of her shows her at the window, watching them receding into the sky until they were as small as stars.
Audio: Our last glimpse of her shows her at the window, watching them receding into the sky until they were as small as stars.

#:~:text=as%20you%20l,.%20
Text:  As you look at Wendy you may see her hair becoming white, and her figure little again, for all this happened long ago. 
Audio: As you look at Wendy, you may see her hair becoming white, and her figure little again, for all this happened long ago.

#:~:text=jane%20is,.%20
Text:  Jane is now a common grown-up, with a daughter called Margaret; and every spring-cleaning time, except when he forgets, Peter comes for Margaret and takes her to the Neverland, where she tells him stories about himself, to which he listens eagerly. 
Audio: Jane is now a common grown-up with a daughter called Margaret. And every spring cleaning time, except when he forgets, Peter comes for Margaret and takes her to the Neverland, where she tells him stories about himself to which he listens eagerly.

#:~:text=when%20ma,.%20
Text:  When Margaret grows up she will have a daughter, who is to be Peter's mother in turn; and thus it will go on, so long as children are gay and innocent and heartless.
Audio: When Margaret grows up, she will have a daughter, who is to be Peter's mother in turn. And so it will go on, so long as children are gay and innocent and heartless. End of Peter Pan by J. M. Berry

